<HEAD>Brom Convicted of First-Degree Murder for Family Ax Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teen-ager accused of killing his parents and younger brother and sister with an ax was found guilty on Tuesday, his 18th birthday, of four counts of first-degree murder. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brom </PERSON>, tried as an adult, had pleaded innocent by reason of mental illness. The Olmsted County District Court jury deliberated about four hours and 45 minutes before returning the guilty verdicts. Brom showed no emotion as the verdict was read shortly after 9 p.m. He was charged with four counts each of first - and second-degree murder in the February 1988 slayings The first-degree murder convictions mean that jurors believe the slayings were premeditated. The trial will move to a second phase Thursday to determine whether <PERSON> Brom </PERSON> was mentally ill at the time and therefore not responsible for his actions. `` Obviously, coming in we knew that phase one was not the strong part of the case for us,'' <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> had agreed that <PERSON> Brom </PERSON> committed the murders but argued that they were not premeditated, said the defense would show that Brom `` is and was mentally ill.'' If Brom is found to have been sane when the murders occurred, he faces a life imprisonment sentence with no chance of parole for 17 -LCB- years on each of the four counts <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Brom </PERSON>, 41, suffered 22 ax wounds in the slayings at the <PERSON> Broms </PERSON>' rural <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> home; <PERSON> Paulette </PERSON>, 41, suffered 18 wounds; 13-year-old <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> had eight wounds and 11-year-old <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> had nine, Dr. <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> testified Tuesday. Olmsted County Attorney <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitz </PERSON> in his closing argument said the number of times each victim was struck by the ax could in itself be enough to prove premeditation. The prosecutor also reminded jurors that <PERSON> Brom </PERSON> had many conversations with friends in the months before the murders in which he discussed killing his family. Brom did not testify. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Brom </PERSON>'s discussions with friends were fantasy. `` The ` plan' consisted of a series of disjointed, illogical, fantasy-like thoughts, flitting in and out of the mind of <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Brom </PERSON> intermixed with thoughts of suicide,'' <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said.
