<HEAD>Republican, Democrat Advance to Congressional Runoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Election Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Democratic state senator and a Republican political aide forced each other into a congressional runoff Tuesday, capturing the top two spots in a special election to fill the seat of the late Rep. <PERSON> Larkin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. Democrat <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> easily took the top two spots in the three-way race, leaving a stunned state Attorney General <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> trailing by more than 15,000 votes. The special election was scheduled after <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> died in a plane crash Aug. 13. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> will face each other in an Oct. 17 runoff. Democrats have been hoping to strip the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> of a seat it has held for more than 16 years. Unofficials returns showed <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> with 51,383 votes, or 42 percent, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> with 45,623, or 37 percent, and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> with 24,497, or 21 percent. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, 36, who ran unsuccessfully for the same seat in 1988, surprised the better-known <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who finished third in the home county where he was district attorney for 12 years. `` We felt all along that we charted a course down the middle that if there was a runoff we would be favored by each side,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` There were a lot more people who voted Democratic than Republican.'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 37, who was criticized for wanting to leave the attorney general's office after only 21 months in office, said he would support <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> in the runoff. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 45, a longtime aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> Lott </PERSON>, said his campaign had `` come from nowhere to be here tonight.'' He promised his supporters `` two weeks of excitment.''
