<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> conferred with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday on the prospects for reducing nuclear and conventional arms and assured the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people they need not fear the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Soviet defense minister was kept waiting a half hour as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> got a briefing from national security adviser <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON> on the attempted coup in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The president was informed after the Oval Office session with <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> that the attempt to oust Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> apparently had failed. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> broke his usual practice of refusing to answer questions during photo opportunities by telling reporters the fighting in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was not `` some American operation.'' The president asked <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> to `` pay my respects to President <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>,'' and said the recent talks with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> were `` very fruitful.'' `` We are satisfied. We've got some problems still,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, but `` things are moving in the direction we wanted.'' <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, emerging 30 minutes later, offered his own rosy assessment of the outlook for arms control. The burly, beribboned general told reporters: `` The main point of my discussions with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president was the question of arms control, the question of reducing conventional armed forces and weapons and the question of promoting a relationship between our two militaries and our two nations.'' Speaking in Russian, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> said: `` The Soviet people are cherishing the best sentiments and feeling towards the Americans. We were comrades at arms during the Second World War and we succeeded in winning a great victory. And now we have no grounds, no reason whatsoever, to go into confrontation -LRB- against -RRB- each other.'' Asked if this meeting had furthered the prospects for an arms pact, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> smiled and said, `` Well, I do n't think I could really assure success at the negotiations within half an hour.'' But he added, `` Our negotiating teams are working in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. I think we are moving forward step by step to the ultimate conclusion of agreements on the questions. Anyhow, we are counting on progress.'' White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said afterward <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had `` reiterated his support for perestroika,'' the Soviet process of reorganization into a more open society, and `` expressed his desire to conclude agreements on conventional forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and on chemical weapons as soon as possible and his hopes for progress in START,'' the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks. If <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> was perturbed at being kept waiting and having events in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> intrude on the Oval Office meeting, he did not show it. Asked if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> favored the removal of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> said, `` I am not prepared to talk on the issue because I am not aware of what happened in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. ... We have not talked about it at all. I ca n't tell you anything more.'' <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> were hoping to reach agreements on several steps to improve the rapidly warming relations between the leadership of the Soviet and American armed forces. `` We are thinking of expanding our exchanges in the military field next year and we are going to draft a whole program which will be designed to promote better understanding between our two militaries and between our peoples,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> took <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, about 62 miles north of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to see the battlefield where Union troops repulsed Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s Confederate soldiers in a bloody three-day battle in July 1863 that marked one of the turning points in the American Civil War. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> is a Civil War buff. After a two-hour tour of the battlefield and viewing its famous landmarks like Devil's Den and the Wheat Field, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> said, `` I wish we would not have any battlefields like this one in the future,'' The <ORGANIZATION> Gettysburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>'s busy schedule called for speeches Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myer </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, near the Pentagon and before the Council on Foreign Relations in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a private group. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> will visit <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION>, a Marine training base in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, on Wednesday, and <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> on Thursday. On Friday he will tour <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bragg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, then return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a news conference with <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION>.
