 <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by a group of Soviets in 1987, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, president of the organization. The compilation by 82 cartoonists offers sketches that are political, satirical and, supposedly, funny to all cultures. Take, for instance, the one showing a husband and wife in their living room with the silhouette of a man in the background. The cut line: `` Relax dear, it's not the police. It's just burglars.'' Then of course there was the Soviet variation of the American `` Mother-in-law-in-Trunk'' jokes. A lady is pictured selling two baskets of apples. Crimean apples were trading slowly at a cheap 35 kopecks apiece. But overpriced Chernobyl apples were selling like hotcakes at 5 rubles each. `` People are buying them for their mothers-in-law, their bosses,'' the caption says. The openness under Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has allowed <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people to `` take up subjects which, until recently, we could only discuss with our friends in our kitchens ... privately,'' said <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Florentiev </PERSON>, foreign editor of <LOCATION> Krokodil </LOCATION>. He urged <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to continue to extend those freedoms. `` If you stop at this stage, it can easily be turned the other way around. You have to go ahead to achieve some positive results,'' <PERSON> Florentiev </PERSON> said.
