<HEAD>Bush's Steel Import Plan Moves to Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The extension of steel import restraints, once a contentious issue in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, is all but assured after an overwhelming <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote to extend restrictions until 1992. Monday's 354-10 vote approved President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s compromise to extend the restrictions on 29 foreign trading partners until April 1992. The `` no'' votes were all Republicans. Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., has introduced a companion measure in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where bipartisan approval is expected soon <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan, announced July 25, called for immediate negotiations with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and other leading steel-exporting nations to extend annual limitations on the volume of steel allowed into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The original pacts, which expired Saturday, were negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in 1984 to give domestic steelmakers breathing space from subsidized, foreign competition. Many steel-district lawmakers pushed the administration to extend the curbs for another five years, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opted for a smaller-scale, 2 -LCB- - year program in deference to steel-using manufacturers The manufacturers argued that the quotas have driven up prices and caused supply shortages of some steel products. The manufacturers had enlisted dozens of lawmakers prepared to argue against a five-year continuation, but the compromise all but eliminated the debate. House opposition came largely from free-traders who felt the steel industry has had enough protection. `` It's not my first choice,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>., who had opposed a longer extension `` Nevertheless, I have to admit it's about as good a compromise as could be achieved.'' Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaydos </PERSON>, D-Pa., who represents a western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> steel district, said the program `` is not a cure-all, but has been the most effective method of dealing with dumped imports. `` This legislation is basically and fundamentally giving the steel industry in this country a little more time to become competitive. And they're well under way,'' <PERSON> Gaydos </PERSON> said. With the old program due to expire Sept. 30, the administration could not afford to wait until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acted to begin the painstaking process of negotiating new import ceilings. Trade representatives from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> were in town last week for meetings on renewing their pacts. Many of the negotiations are already complete, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>. Even though <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has n't finished work on the bill, she said steel imports would continue to be monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. No details on individual pacts have been announced. In a prepared statement Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> applauded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators for their work but stressed that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> program should not preclude American steelmakers from filing unfair trade complaints, if necessary, against foreign governments. Voting against the bill were Republicans <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Armey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohrbacher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stump </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Petri </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>.
