<HEAD>Taiwan Establishes Ties with Liberia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> have normalized relations 12 years after the African nation switched recognition from <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> to the rival Communist government in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, officials say. The late Monday night announcement by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Lien </PERSON> <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> represents a breakthrough for the Nationalist government's new flexible policy of seeking diplomatic ties with countries that already have relations with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lien </PERSON> attributed <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s diplomatic victory to its `` making more progress politically, economically and socially'' than Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The official <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, quoting unnamed sources, said <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> had agreed to offer <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> a $ 200 million loan. Foreign Ministry officials declined comment. The re-establishment of ties between <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> comes three months after <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> established ties with <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> subsequently suspended diplomatic relations with the tiny <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island. There was no immediate reaction from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>'s decision <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s latest moves come after decades of diplomatic reversals in which the overwhelming majority of nations chose to recognize the Communists in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> instead of the Nationalists in <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION>. Both governments have claimed to be the legitimate ruler of all <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the Communists defeated the Nationalists in a civil war that ended in 1949. The number of countries with formal ties to the Nationalist government has dropped from more than 50 in 1949 to 24, not including <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, which is among the 134 countries that recognize <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> told a news conference Monday night that <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> would sign a formal communique on setting up diplomatic ties in a few days. The two countries agreed to pursue normalization in January, he said. Communist Chinese leaders have criticized <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s flexible diplomacy as a plan to promote two separate Chinas, a claim the Nationalist officials deny. <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, with a population of 2.5 million, is an agricultural country that relies on the exports of coffee, lumber and rubber. <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> imported $ 24 million of industrial products from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1988. Its exports to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> totaled $ 270,000.
