<HEAD>The Raleigh Times to Cease Publication Nov. 30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> will stop publishing after 110 years so its resources can be used to improve its sister paper, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Observer, said the publisher, who mourned the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as `` a daggone good newspaper.'' `` It was a pretty wrenching decision,'' said Publisher <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who is also president of the <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The reader has voted, and what they have said is, they want the <ORGANIZATION> N </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; O, a morning paper, instead of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, an afternoon paper.'' The Times will cease publication Nov. 30, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said Monday. An internal task force that reviewed the performance of both papers, reader preferences and other factors recommended closing the Times as part of a plan to expand and improve The News & amp; Observer, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. Afternoon dailies across the country have been in decline in recent years as publishers have found it increasingly difficult to make timely delivery to the suburbs and readers have opted for television news in the evening. The News & amp; Observer has a daily circulation of 145,000, compared with the Times' 21,500. `` Just not enough people wanted to read it,'' <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. `` I thought it was a daggone good newspaper.'' `` For several years, we have watched as afternoon dailies in metropolitan areas closed,'' the publisher said. `` We can not make the improvements The News & amp; Observer needs and still publish a quality afternoon newspaper.'' The additional staff will be used to improve The News & amp; Observer's coverage of surrounding <LOCATION> Wake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and nearby <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said. That and other improvements could not be made as long as the Times was being published, he said. <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> said no layoffs are expected. The news staffs of the papers were combined in 1987. The Times began in 1879 as the Raleigh Evening Visitor. After merging with two competitors, it was renamed The <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in 1901. The Park family of <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION> purchased <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in 1911, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> A. Park served as editor and publisher for 44 years. The Times was sold to the <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Observer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1955.
