 The commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surface </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is conducting a disciplinary inquiry aboard the USS Iowa, the battleship on which 47 sailors were killed in an April explosion, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> sources say. Vice Adm. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnell </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> is conducting the non-judicial inquiry to determine whether the captain and several other officers should be punished, the sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said after a lengthy study that gunner's mate <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartwig </PERSON> `` most likely'' caused the explosion in the battleship's No 2 gun turret by inserting a detonator between two powder bags But the investigation led by Rear Adm. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> also alleged numerous lax procedures aboard the ship, including unauthorized experimentation with extra-strength gunpowder and projectile loads. <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON> said the officers had failed to qualify enough sailors for their specific duties in the gun turret and that many safety procedures had been circumvented. He recommended that Capt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Moosally </PERSON> and four other high-ranking men be relieved and disciplined. However, his superiors decided the men should receive non-judicial punishment through the mast procedure. <PERSON> Donnell </PERSON>, who was one of the endorsing officers of the final <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> report, countered <PERSON> Milligan </PERSON>'s recommendation that the five men be removed, arguing that the infractions amounted to `` a failure of leadership'' on the captain's part but were `` a marked departure from otherwise outstanding performance.'' <PERSON> Donnell </PERSON> is expected to conduct his inquiries separately for each of the men, and the procedures are expected to last several days, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> source said. The USS Iowa is in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>. Besides <PERSON> Moosally </PERSON>, the men include the ship's executive officer, the weapons officer and a master chief petty officer who was found to have experimented with the gun firings. The gunnery officer requested and received a transfer. A separate procedure is expected to be conducted for him later, the source said.
