 The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Tuesday despite intervention by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s central bank, while stock prices slipped. The dollar opened at 139.72 yen, up 0.42 yen from Monday's close of 139.30 yen, and closed at 140.65 yen, up 1.35 yen. It traded in a range of 139.70 to 140.68 yen. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-share <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> lost 256.60 points, or 0.72 percent, to close at 35,366.37 points. Currency traders said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> intervened several times, selling dollars for yen at about the 140-yen level. `` The dollar was moving slightly upward as market players corrected their dollar-holding positions,'' said a trader with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said participants were buying back dollars they had sold earlier, following talks last week among monetary officials from seven key currency nations, known as the Group of Seven. The officials agreed to strengthen coordinated monetary intervention to push the dollar lower. <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> investors were focusing on selling West German marks and buying the yen, thus helping the dollar to strengthen against other major currencies, the Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trader said. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> was likely to prevent a further rise in the dollar. The amount of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>'s purchases was not immediately known. The central bank does not normally comment officially on its market intervention. On the stock exchange, traders said many participants stayed on the sidelines watching the currency market. Dealers said the weakening yen discouraged Japanese investors, and the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> index fell as they sold to take profits. An analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Yamaichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, who spoke on condition of anonmyity, said institutional investors also held back because of a lack of trading focus.
