<FIRST>r i PM-BodyPolitics     10-03 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Body Politics,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drama Over Marcos Body Part Of Filipino Political Tradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The standoff over where to bury <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is the latest example of `` body politics'' _ a Filipino game <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s supporters once played themselves to rally a nation and topple a dictator. Rules of the game demand protracted wakes, vigils and novenas. Players include grieving relatives who regale reporters, television audiences and crowds of spectators with tales of injustice and appeals to respect Filipino tradition. The object is to play on the Filipino's almost mystical respect for the dead to promote the cause of the deceased and the fortunes of the living. Since <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> died Thursday in exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> radio and television stations and newspapers have in daily reports showed the grieving widow, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, standing before the former president's open coffin. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has vowed to do all she can to return her husband's remains to his homeland, despite President <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s refusal to allow his burial here `` I also ask for your prayers to give me strength to that I will see the victory of my struggle to clear the name of President <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and the whole nation,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> said in a radio interview broadcast here today. The scene in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> is an ironic parody of the events of six years ago, after Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s husband, Sen. <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, was murdered moments after returning from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to challenge <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. After the Aug. 21, 1983 slaying, the <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> family held a nine-day wake during which thousands of people filed by to view the body, still dressed in the blood-soaked clothes in which <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> died. Perhaps two million people turned out for the funeral, as <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s body was paraded over a 19-mile route aboard a 10-wheel flatbed truck. The outrage over the killing galvanized anti-Marcos sentiment and paved the way for the uprising which toppled the longtime president and propelled <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s widow into the presidency on Feb. 25, 1986. Body politics has been played by lesser figures too. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' mother, <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON>, died on May 4, 1988. But <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' followers hoped to use her death to dramatize their leader's exile and embarass the government into allowing him to return. The ploy failed. Mrs. <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON> remains unburied, lying in an open casket in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION>, 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Die-hard <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' loyalists carry on a vigil which has been largely forgotten. The military has also discovered the merits of body politics in its campaign to discredit the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which is waging a 20-year insurgency. Under <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, the military tried to hide figures on the number of soldiers killed by both Communist insurgents and Moslem guerrillas in the south. But no more. On Sept. 3, rebels killed 13 soldiers working on a highway construction project in <LOCATION> Quezon </LOCATION> province. As commanders spoke of this `` outrage,'' television cameras panned the flag-draped corpses and grieving widows. The military also claims the rebels have been carrying out a protracted purge of their ranks and have killed scores of party members suspected of disloyalty. With the discovery of every `` killing field'' _ where rebels allegedly bury the victims _ the military encourages television cameras to film as bones are unearthed from shallow graves. At dinner-hour newscasts, Filipinos watch as elderly peasants weep over the bones, supposedly of their sons and daughters `` executed'' by the rebels.
