<FIRST>r a PM-RaceSchool Bjt   10-03 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Race School, Bjt,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>School to Teach Better Race Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A middle school has transformed itself into a laboratory on ways to improve race relations where teachers hope to erase past tensions and perhaps serve as a model for the rest of the nation. `` Some kids' cultural upbringing is different. Some of it is unconscious. We need to learn to understand each other better,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Pipkin </PERSON>, principal of the <ORGANIZATION> Prospect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Multiracial </ORGANIZATION>, Multi-ethnic and Multicultural Education. Prospect teachers _ and their sixth -, seventh - and eighth-grade students _ are learning the fine points of dealing with whites, blacks, Asians, Hispanics, and Native The students, split almost evenly among whites and blacks, will learn about the cultures of other races and ethnic groups in hope they will find their differences enlightening rather than divisive. The school, in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s racially balanced <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> section, will retain its traditional curriculum, but also will teach students to recognize racism and its consequences. Teachers also will try to provide lessons free of racial bias. Another part of the program could prove more controversial. Since some studies indicate children of different races and cultural backgrounds have different learning styles, teachers will be taught to expand their repertoire of teaching methods, said psychologist <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>'s director of multicultural education `` White children tend to be abstract learners. In the area of mathematics, for example, they can learn by being exposed to a formula,'' <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said. Black children, in general, learn best when the lesson is embedded within a context or accompanied by examples, he said. `` This is an oversimplification, of course,'' he said. `` There are always wide variations and exceptions.'' Attempts to put these theories to work elsewhere have offended blacks. `` People tend to equate abstract learning with higher thinking, which is n't the case at all,'' <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said. Administrators hope the program will generate new ideas that can be used in other schools in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and, perhaps, across the country. `` We want a program that will celebrate diversity and encourage kids to be proud of their background and knowledgeable about their cultural heritage,'' <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said. The first year of the program will involve mostly training and planning. Next September, however, the center will begin projects designed to enhance students' self-esteem, teach the histories of different minorities and sensitize teachers to their own racial attitudes. About 52 percent of the district's 39,500 students are black and 47 percent are white. One percent come from other minority groups. Of Prospect's 625 students, 48 percent are black. The district invited teachers to apply to work in the new program, and 90 percent of Prospect's teachers and staff are new to the school. This year 35 percent, or 21, of the school's 59 full-time teachers are black and the rest are white. The idea for the changes sprang from a study that found black male students in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> got suspended from schools more often than others. `` We also had a couple of incidents of racism,'' <PERSON> Pipkin </PERSON> said. `` We had some teachers making blatant remarks about Afro-American kids and episodes between back and while students _ some racial name calling.'' Changes also were suggested by business and community advisers concerned about black students' complaints of racial harassment at colleges and universities, including <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
