ion goes well beyond that proposal,'' <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> said of the subcommittee plan. Though the provisions would make auto standards far more stringent, they would improve air quality a mere 1 percent compared with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal, he said. <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> also said there are serious safety questions about vapor recovery systems that would be mandated under the provisions. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> also criticized subcommittee proposal. `` First, the proposed standards stretch the limits of technological feasibility, and we presently lack assurance that these standards can be met at the levels of reliability and quality the American public demands,'' <PERSON> Houston </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucksbaum </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, praised the proposal. `` We're very encouraged by this compromise,'' <PERSON> Bucksbaum </PERSON> said. `` It's an excellent first step particularly in area of controlling smaller pollutants.''
