<HEAD>Efforts to Prevent Oil Drilling in Alaska's Bristol Bay Shift to
Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s efforts to prevent oil and gas exploration in the rich fishing grounds of <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> focused on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> declined to hear the state's latest appeal The court Monday left intact rulings that allowed the federal government to sell $ 94 million worth of exploratory leases last year on 5.6 million acres of the bay off southwest <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. `` It means, as we suspected, that the battle has shifted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which is moving in the direction of protecting <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> from development,'' said <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, executive director of the environmental group Trustees for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. State Attorney General <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Baily </PERSON> said he was not surprised by the court's action: `` We've been focusing on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, in part, because we did n't want to trust all of our eggs in the basket of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.'' State officials, environmental groups and fishing organizations have said the relatively small chance of finding large amounts of oil under <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> is not worth the risk of an oil spill to fish and wildlife. They also contend that a spill would do more environmental harm there than the Exxon Valdez spill did to Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. The March 24 tanker disaster, the nation's worst oil spill, forced the closure of several fishing areas. <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> supports the world's largest red salmon fishery, worth more than $ 1 billion annually, and the largest