<HEAD>Government-Opposition Talks Over Rent Boycott Called Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government officials have for the first time negotiated with leading anti-apartheid leaders about ending the 3-year-old rent boycott in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, the country's largest black township. Business Day, a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> daily, today described the talks as the highest-level bargaining session ever held between the white-controlled government and major anti-apartheid activisits. It quoted one unidentified activist as calling Monday's parley, in which the government offered to waive some unpaid rent, `` an unprecedented breakthrough'' because the activists were accepted as primary negotiating partners. The boycott has been one of the most effective protests by blacks since a national state of emergency was declared in June 1986. <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, home to an estimated 2.5 million blacks on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, has been the hardest-hit of several townships affected by rent boycotts. It has lost more than $ 100 million in revenue. The government delegation, led by <ORGANIZATION> Transvaal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> Danie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hough </PERSON>, met in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> city councilors and prominent activists, including Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>; the Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Albertina </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON>, co-president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> anti-apartheid coalition. <PERSON> Hough </PERSON> said the activists `` have a very important role to play'' _ an unusual government acknowledgement of the influence enjoyed by militant leaders within black communities. He said the delegations would meet again. The government could not accept demands to write off all unpaid rent, but a partial waiver could be negotiated, <PERSON> Hough </PERSON> said. He offered to negotiate ways to transfer ownership of rented houses to their occupants, another demand of the activists. <PERSON> Hough </PERSON> said a demand that <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> be unified to share tax revenue was `` probably impractical.'' <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, the activists' spokesman, said the meeting showed that `` we can resolve problems by talking rather than relegating the solution to the police.'' Police have tried periodically to evict boycotters from their homes. One such campaign, in August 1986, led to confrontations in which more than 20 blacks were killed by police gunfire. Under apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
