> provide any intelligence information to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1971?'' asked plaintiff's attorney <PERSON> Cyriac </PERSON> <PERSON> Kappil </PERSON>. `` Not to the best of my knowledge,'' said <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> testified that in 1971, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government believed <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was about to invade <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, now known as <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, based on intelligence reports. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> became national security advisor in 1969 and served as secretary of state from 1973 to 1977. Under cross-examination by <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> said he was n't told the names of paid <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> informants. `` You do n't know the name of a single person who's gotten such funds, correct?'' questioned defense attorney <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>. `` Correct,'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> replied. `` Is it correct that you do n't know whether, in fact, government officials said that to Mr. <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON>?'' <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> later asked, referring to <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON>'s contention that government sources had identified <PERSON> Desai </PERSON> as a paid informant. `` Or whether they existed,'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> replied. `` I know nothing about them.'' <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> was the awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1973 for his part in ending the war in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hersh </PERSON> won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970 for his reporting on the My Lai massacre in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.
