<HEAD>Five Amateur Stargazers Selected to Use Space Telescope</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, `The 250,000 ...' to CORRECT telescope's
weight to 24,000 pounds.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five amateur astronomers are preparing for an undreamed-of opportunity to go eyeball to eyeball with the universe using what will be the world's most powerful space telescope. In a gesture of appreciation for scientific contributions by hobbyists using backyard telescopes, the <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> has offered 20 hours of observing time on the <ORGANIZATION> Hubble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION> to projects designed by amateurs. The telescope, to be launched on a space shuttle in March, is a joint project of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The project, based at <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, is expected to cost about $ 750 million and has been in planning stages for a decade. For someone who is not a professional astronomer, the odds of getting to use the telescope are comparable to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jetson </PERSON>'s chances of getting a raise from his tightfisted boss at Spacely Sprockets `` I would guess every amateur astronomer would love to use it,'' said one of those selected, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Secosky </PERSON>, a science teacher from <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` I never thought I'd get to use an instrument like this.'' But astronomy is one of the few scientific fields in which amateurs make significant breakthroughs. For example, <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubble </PERSON>, the American astronomer for whom the telescope is named, developed his theory of the expanding universe in cooperation with <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Humason </PERSON>, a former janitor, mule driver and high-school dropout. `` In actuality, outer space begins in your back yard. All you need is a good pair of binoculars to get started,'' said <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Kandefer </PERSON>, an electrical engineer from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, who also was chosen. Others selected include a computer expert and a homemaker. Professionals already have overbooked time on the telescope, the first major optical telescope that will be permanently stationed in low Earth orbit, said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Villard </PERSON>, an institute spokesman. The 24,000-pound instrument, about the size of a bus, has a 2.4-meter mirror that will gather enough light to enable researchers to make images of things that are 25 to 50 times fainter than the dimmest object previously seen. Free of the atmosphere's distortion of distant light and the Earth's tendency to absorb the extreme ends of the light spectrum, the telescope will produce pictures 10 times clearer than anything available on the ground, <PERSON> Villard </PERSON> said. `` If your eyes were as good as the telescope, you would be able to see a dime 20 miles away _ and know it was a dime,'' <PERSON> Villard </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Secosky </PERSON>, 42, is interested in why <PERSON> Jupter </PERSON>'s moon Io sometimes appears brighter as it emerges from the planet's frigid shadow. He thinks his observations may detect evidence of frost forming on the moon. <PERSON> Kandefer </PERSON>'s regular job is working on flight controls and guidance sensors, but the 42-year-old engineer spends his free time trying to learn about steller magnetic fields 10 times stronger than the sun's. The only woman in the group, <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, was half a dozen years into an accounting career when she decided to take time off to raise her two children and fell in love with astronomy through <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> correspondence courses. Her goal is to find huge planets taking form around stars, a process scientists suspect is occurring but can not prove because it is so difficult to distinguish any object that close to a star's brightness <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> hopes to find planets five to 10 times larger than Jupiter that release enormous amounts of energy, detectable to a telescope as heat. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterner </PERSON>, a 37-year-old computer scientist at <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION>, will test his theory that luminescent arcs discovered in a distant galaxy cluster are made of stars. Most astronomers consider such arcs to be optical illusions caused by gravity bending starlight. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON>, who works at a science museum in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, hopes to detect a hypothetical mass of primordial material surrounding a star where comets could take form. `` We are n't professional scientists and we would not qualify as observers under the regular procedures,'' <PERSON> Hewitt </PERSON> said. `` This is an incredible opportunity for an amateur astronomer on what is esentially the most capable astronomical instrument ever created.''
