<HEAD>Communist Party Tries to Fit Into New Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf, `The party ...' with quotes
from party secretary.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders began meeting today to discuss ways to overhaul their image and win support of a citizenry that has embraced the new Solidarity-led government. The party, the first ever to lose control of a Soviet bloc government, is even considering changing its official name _ the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ as part of its effort to improve its standing with the populace. Opposition candidates virtually swept all seats available to non-Communist candidates in June's partially free elections. Pro-Solidarity lawmakers eventually put together a coalition with parties that were once allied with the Communists, resulting last month in the first non-Communist government in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. In 1993, elections are to be fully democratic, and the Communists are trying desperately to find a place in the new <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, which is embracing democratic reforms in a scramble to salvage its collapsing economy. A survey released at the start of today's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> plenum showed that fully 72 percent of the party members favor changing its name to reflect a change in image and purpose. Party leaders were expected to set a date and an agenda for a party congress, which would enact the changes recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The congress would be a meeting of 1,000 to 2,000 delegates elected from among the 2 million rank-and-file party members. The congress is expected to be set for mid-February, said a party official, demanding anonymity. The party official said the internal party survey, in which more than half the members took part, showed there was a strong danger that the party could split. Party chief <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> has warned that a split could end the party. Accordingly, the plenum has adopted the slogan `` Unity at Any Price.'' The official described the split within party ranks as being between the leadership and the rank-and-file members, who favor radical reform, and the `` middle level'' party organizers who want to maintain a traditional party. The party official said the goal is to create a party that will be attractive to voters in the 1993 elections. The party hopes to do well enough in the voting to emerge as the dominant partner in a leftist coalition, he said. Party Secretary <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the party is inviting society to `` create the party with us,'' and that the party must strive to find an identity which will give it a popular base. `` The question is whether the Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> can fulfill the aspirations of the part of Polish society which is left-leaning,'' he said. The plenum also is expected to support internal party democracy, a state-dominated economy for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and instigate a shakeup of the ruling Politburo. It would be the second leadership shuffle since July, the official said. `` If we remain in unity for three months, then we exist and we will win,'' the official said. `` If the party is destroyed, then the left does not exist for practical purposes for many years.'' The pro-Solidarity newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> reported today that the draft resolution for the plenum called for development of a `` humanitarian, democratic and effective socialism.'' On the economic front, the draft favors a multi-sector economy dominated by the state-run economy. It opposes selling off state enterprises, a chief economic goal of the Solidarity-led government. The draft also `` obliges all party cells to create conditions for free expression of different views,'' the newspaper said.
