<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s abortion rights supporters is not taking part in a key abortion case before the court in its 1989-90 term. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> disqualified himself from the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case, one of three the high court is considering this term, for unstated reasons, court spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> had not disqualified himself when the justices agreed last July 3 to review the case. But a minor court order issued Monday in the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case, which deals with abortion clinic regulations, noted that <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> did not participate. His absence will not change the outcome of the case if the justices line up as they did last July when voting 5-4 to let states make abortion harder to get. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was one of the dissenters. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> still is the key vote. If she votes against the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> law, the outcome could be a 4-4 `` pro-choice'' victory. If she votes in favor of the law, the outcome could be a 5-3 anti-abortion victory. A 4-4 split would not set any legal precedent outside <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. The case focuses on a state law that would require abortion clinics to add services and equipment now found only in hospitals. The law could force many clinics to close down, and could add up to $ 50 to the cost of an abrtion performed in the first three months of pregnancy. In invalidating the law, lower courts said it violated a portion of the 1973 ruling in <LOCATION> Roe </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> that limited state regulation over first-trimester abortions. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials are not asking the justices to use the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case to reverse <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, but legal experts say the court's ruling could chip away at the trimester-by-trimester approach taken in the 1973 decision. The two other abortion cases under high court study this term focus on parental notification requirements for unwed minors seeking to end their pregnancies in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has not disqualified himself from those cases. The <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> case is Turnock vs. <PERSON> Ragsdale </PERSON>, 88-790.
