<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will vote to approve President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s decrees allowing extradition of top drug suspects to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and confiscation of their property, national television reported. The television program TV Hoy, quoting court sources, reported Monday night that a majority of 24 justices on the Court supported the decrees. The deadline for the court to rule was today, but normally several days pass before court rulings are made public. Seven bombs exploded in Colombian cities Monday night, two in the <LOCATION> Carribbean </LOCATION> coast city of <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION>, three in the port city of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION> and two in the capital of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, national police said. Two people were injured in <LOCATION> Barranquilla </LOCATION> and two more in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marta </LOCATION>, the police said. They were part of a daily wave of bombings presumably set by drug traffickers. A <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling allowing extraditions would strengthen the Barco administration in its war against the drug lords, and would help allay fears that the court could undermine the anti-drug crackdown. TV <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON> said, however, that the court would declare unconstitutional an additional decree allowing the <LOCATION> Colombian </LOCATION> army to raid drug traffickers' property at will. It said the court will support the government's right to confiscate property from drug traffickers but will require that it go through judicial channels. The court will not decide on the legality of property already seized, leaving that issue for lower courts, TV Hoy said. As of a week ago, the army had seized 1,056 homes, ranches, mansions office buildings and other property allegedly belonging to drug traffickers. The administration's main weapon in the drug war is its power to extradite suspected drug figures who have repeatedly shown their ability to escape justice in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has a list of 80 Colombians it wants extradited to face drug charges, but it has disclosed the names of only the top 12. In 1984 the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, ruling on a technicality, declared extraditions to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> unconstitutional. The court has not dealt favorably with other important Barco decrees. Before Barco declared war on the traffickers Aug. 19, the court had knocked down seven decrees he issued in attempts to deal with both guerrillas and drug traffickers. The most important of earlier decrees declared unconstitutional was one creating a special tribunal within the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to deal with drug trafficking and other cases that present security problems for lower court judges. Barco wanted to remove certain cases from the jurisdiction of the lower court judges, who often have been threatened or killed while handling drug trafficking cases. In the last 10 years 220 court employees, including 41 judges, have been killed, many of them by drug traffickers.
