<FIRST>r a PM-SpermBanks     10-03 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sperm Banks,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Prompts Ban on Sperm Donations From Homosexuals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gay men and intravenous drug users have been barred from donating sperm in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state because of worries about AIDS. The regulations, which took effect this week, exclude any man from donating to a sperm bank if he has had homosexual activity, intravenous drug use or sex with a `` high risk'' person since 1977. The same people already are barred from donating blood in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state for the same reason, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardineer </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> associate director for regulatory affairs. The regulations for the first time also require sperm banks to obtain state licenses. `` Women who choose to undergo artificial insemination should not be subjected to unnecessary risks for serious and even fatal illnesses,'' <PERSON> Gardineer </PERSON> said. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which chiefly afflicts homosexual men and intravenous drug users, is spread most often through sex; needles or syringes shared by drug abusers; infected blood, and from pregnant women to their offspring. <PERSON> Gardineer </PERSON> said there have been cases of infants who contracted AIDS because of donated sperm, but she could not say how many. The prohibition was recommended by several doctors' groups. The rules require extensive medical background checks on donors and tests on the donated sperm. All donations must be frozen for six months, the time it takes for someone infected with the AIDS virus to develop antibodies that show up in tests. The rules do n't apply in cases where a man is donating sperm for a specific woman, such as his wife, because donors have a right to privacy, officials said. The growing popularity of artificial insemination made the rules necessary, said <PERSON> Gardineer </PERSON>. In 1986, about 60,000 women gave birth as a result of artificial insemination in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. She estimated there are five sperm banks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state, but said the number is n't certain because they have n't been licensed. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state has 25,000 confirmed AIDS cases, about a quarter of the nation's total. Most of them are in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
