<HEAD>Tanker Captain Says He Had No Lookout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The captain of a Greek tanker that hit a reef and spilled 289,000 gallons of heating oil into <PERSON> Narragansett </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON> testified today he did not have the required lookout on the bridge when entering the harbor. <PERSON> Iakovos </PERSON> <PERSON> Georgoudis </PERSON>, 43, of <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> also said maps made it unclear exactly where ships are to pick up their harbor pilots to guide the vessel into port. The vessel ran aground off <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> on June 23 before a pilot boarded. The captain of the World Prodigy told a board of inquiry convened by the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> that his company and Greek regulations required a lookout when entering a harbor. `` There was no one,'' however, because the lookout had been sent to help lower the ladder so the pilot could board, <PERSON> Georgoudis </PERSON> said through interpreters. He said he was doing nearly all the work on the bridge at the time of the accident, including lookout and navigator. `` I was everything,'' he said. <PERSON> Georgoudis </PERSON> had refused to testify previously before the panel, citing his right against self-incrimination. That no longer was an issue after he pleaded guilty in August and September to state and federal pollution charges. The captain was fined a total of $ 30,500. A charge of failing to have a pilot on board was dropped as part of the plea bargain. Authorities said the commonly agreed-on pickup point is actually inside the area where state law requires a pilot. The tanker's owner, <ORGANIZATION> Ballard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor and was ordered to pay $ 500,000. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON> has said it was clear that <PERSON> Georgoudis </PERSON> had too many duties at the time and the accident was caused by negligence, not by recklessness. Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> said $ 125,000 of <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON>'s fine would be used to help <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s fishing industry.
