<HEAD>Abortion Restrictions Proposed in Pennsylvania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s anti-abortion forces today introduced a bill to put sweeping restrictions on abortion At a news conference, Republican Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Freind </PERSON> said the legislation would directly challenge <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> and give the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> another chance to overturn its 1973 ruling establishing the right to an abortion. Earlier this year, the high court gave states broader powers to restrict abortions. Freind's bill, which has the backing of Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, could be the first to be adopted since that ruling in July. The suburban <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> legislator, who arrived at the news conference under police guard and was picketed by abortion-rights advocates, said his bill would: _ Require a 24-hour waiting period before a woman can have an abortion. _ Outlaw all abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy except to save the woman's life. _ Ban abortions by women who want to choose the sex of a child. _ Require notification of the spouse before a woman has an abortion. The high court has previously rejected such notification laws. `` We are very encouraged that the legislation will be passed by the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Legislature,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beliveau </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Pro-Life Federation. Abortion-rights advocates today introduced their legislative package, including a proposed constitutional amendment establishing a right to an abortion. The pro-choice bills would also restore government funding for poor women who have medically necessary abortions and would weaken a law requiring parental notification or a court order before a minor can obtain an abortion. That provision is not in effect because it is under court review. While <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> historically has opposed abortion, pro-choice advocates said today that most <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> voters support the right to choose. In a poll of 500 likely voters, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> said 60 percent favored keeping abortion legal, while 33 percent wanted to outlaw it. `` This data shows how dramatically out-of-step <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s officials are with their constituents on abortion,'' said <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, the league's executive director `` The political atmosphere surrounding choice is more highly charged than ever. ... Politicians in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> who support abortion restrictions in 1989 may well be voted out of office in 1990.'' The poll, taken Sept. 25-28 by <ORGANIZATION> Hickman-Maslin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has a margin of error of plus or minus 4.4 points.
