<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> PORT-AU-PRINCE </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The government cut in half the salary of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s leader, and top officials' salaries were slashed up to 33 percent in an effort to reduce the budget deficit, an official newspaper said Tuesday. An <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> communique published in L'Union, the government's daily newspaper, said Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril's $ 10,000 a month salary has been reduced to $ 5,000. It said a 33 percent salary cut would apply to <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> ministers, who earned $ 3,500 before the cut. The salary cuts, effective for six months starting Oct. 1, `` are part of a strategy which aims at lessening the ills of the present economic crisis,'' the communique said. A 20 percent salary cut was applied to top civil servants earning $ 1,500 monthly, and 10 percent was deducted from the salaries of public workers earning $ 1,000 monthly. The average annual income in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> is less than $ 300 a year. <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, one of the world's poorest nations, has a deficit of $ 60 million. The foreign debt is $ 800 million, three times more than the annual budget. Government salaries account for 75 percent of the budget, <PERSON> L'Union </PERSON> said. The move came a week after a 24-hour strike shut down virtually all businesses and transport in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nation of 6 million. The strike was called by leftist and conservative groups to protest austerity measures imposed to win a $ 26.5 million loan from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. The day after the strike, <PERSON> Avril </PERSON> conceded the strikers' demands were just but said he had no choice but to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> because `` we had a knife to our throat.''
