<FIRST>r a AM-APME-Janensch     10-03 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-Janensch,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Editors Urged To Be `Fanatical' on Community Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's newspaper editors must be `` fanatical'' about developing ties to their communities if they hope to reverse a slide in readership, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors said Tuesday. `` We must get closer to our communities,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON>, editor and general manager of The <ORGANIZATION> Rockland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal-News </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s suburban <LOCATION> Rockland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` Call it what you will _ customer obsession, putting the reader first, serving the constituents _ we must do it better,'' he said. `` I firmly believe that if we build a strong rapport with our communities, we will prosper. If we do n't, we will fade away.'' As he opened the annual APME convention, <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> pointed to figures showing that newspaper readership is declining. `` In 1967, about 73 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> adults said they read a newspaper every day,'' he said. `` Last year, the number was down to 51 percent.'' <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> said steadily declining readership `` confronts us with the most serious problem facing newspapers today'' and said it even hits markets where the economy is booming. `` If you are lucky enough to be in a growing market and your circulation is going up, you may think you do n't have a problem,'' he said. `` Wrong. Even where circulation is going up, net newspaper penetration is going down. There are no exceptions.'' Frequently lost in the daily pressure of publishing, <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> said, is the need to establish links between a newspaper and the community. `` We all know the answer, but we lose sight of it solving our day-to-day newsroom problems,'' he said. `` We lose sight of it wrestling with budgets, performance evaluations and other administrative matters.'' `` Do you hear what the people in your community are saying about your newspaper?'' he asked. `` Do you know what they like? Do you know what ticks them off?'' Surveying readers ca n't substitute for basics of business, such as customer service, he said. `` Readership surveys can be useful, but they are n't enough,'' <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> said. `` Surveys ca n't halt sliding readership unless the editor and the editor's staff are fanatical about getting close to the community.'' While many are captivated by national news and big-name events, most of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s newspapers survive by providing residents of the community with information they need in their daily lives, he said. `` Is your newspaper first and foremost a local newspaper?'' asked <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON>. `` Do you care as much about the expansion of a local business as you do about the national trade deficit?'' In addition to building community ties, <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> said, a newspaper's staff must reflect the paper's market. `` Does your staff at all levels reflect the racial and ethnic diversity of your target readership?'' he asked the editors. `` Are about half of your staffers women? Do your staffers have roots in the community?'' Without that commitment to community, <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> said, the steady decline in newspaper readership will inevitably continue, costing newspapers advertising revenue, and that in turn tightens budgets and damages the news product. `` The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> might be able to survive with 10 or 15 percent of its primary market, but can you?'' <PERSON> Janensch </PERSON> asked editors. The <ORGANIZATION> APME </ORGANIZATION> is an association of editors from member newspapers of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
