<HEAD>Parents Settle Over Daughter's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parents of a 4-year-old who died after a swimming lesson described as strenuous have settled a lawsuit against instructors and a beach resort for nearly $ 1 million. `` We still ca n't believe it happened,'' said <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, who watched at poolside while instructors huddled over her daughter, Amber <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, after she lost consciousness during a 50-yard swim. Amber was taking a swimming lesson in August 1987 from <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Symons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatton </PERSON> at the Tides Hotel and Bath Club Resort in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Redington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. According to the lawsuit, <PERSON> Hatton </PERSON> made her swim two laps in the 75-foot pool. During the second lap the child, who had tearfully complained of fatigue, lost consciousness and stopped breathing with an instructor only a couple feet from her. The mother of another child in the class and an instruction performed cardiopulmonary resuscitation until paramedics arrived, but Amber never breathed on her own again and was placed on life support equipment. She was removed from the equipment eight days later and died. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> filed suit against the instructors and <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, which owns the resort, alleging negligence. They settled Monday for $ 950,000. The couple said they will wage a personal campaign for state and national laws requiring instructors and lifeguards be certified in lifesaving skills and CPR. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, attorney for the resort and the instructors, said the instructors were certified in lifesaving and CPR, more qualified than was required by either <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Swimming, a sanctioning association, or <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law. The last thing Mrs. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> remembers is Amber asking: `` Mommy, how much longer is class? I do n't want to swim the long way.'' `` I'll always have a problem with that,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, 32, said through tears. Family attorney <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> said the couple decided to settle rather than take the matter to court this week because of the stress a trial would bring. `` They would have been reliving this thing 1,000 times.'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said the hotel is looking at the swim program to see if changes need to be made. Hotel management `` wanted to get all this over and done with first,'' he said. <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> denied there were serious flaws with the program. `` If it were so deficient, how did it function for 35 years,'' teaching 8,000 to 10,000 swimmers in three generations, without another death, he asked.
