<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Scene     10-03 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Scene,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Left Blood-Spattered, Unconscious As 300 Storm Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 East Germans were left blood-spattered and some even unconscious Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> as nearly 300 of the most desperate fought police, broke through barricades and scaled a fence in their bid for freedom. `` This is pandemonium,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> assistant handling injured refugees on the embassy grounds. Early Tuesday, officials closed the embassy, leaving nearly 1,000 people stranded outside the baroque <PERSON> Lobkowicz </PERSON> Palace that houses it. Between 4,000 and 5,000 people, including some 1,500 children, were packed into the compound at the time, and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officials feared sanitation problems. Shortly after noon, the desperation peaked. Witnesses saw groups of newcomers rush toward the fence of the compound, which was blocked by a police barricade. When police tried to stop them, the refugees pulled down the barricade. Police resorted to their truncheons. `` They clubbed like mad,'' a Czechoslovak eyewitness reported. More people from the waiting crowd surged toward where the beatings took place. In only minutes, almost 300 thronged the narrow passage toward a six-foot fence into the embassy garden. Police beat them as they passed, and many reached the fence bleeding. Those who broke through scaled the fence. Refugees quickly built `` a human ladder'' to help many clear the hurdle, the witnesses said. Many got caught on the sharp spikes at the top of the fence and others jumped or fell head-first to the ground. Some were later seen lying unconscious inside the compound, the witnesses said. Outside the embassy, families with small children were unable to get inside. They said they feared police retaliation. Later, when the situation had calmed down somewhat, young men were still seen climbing the embassy facade from a truck. They were pulled in through windows by other refugees.
</TEXT>
