<HEAD>Pool Closed after Lifeguards Fall Ill with Rare Respiratory Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal health officials will test water from a city pool closed Tuesday in a search for the cause of a rare respiratory problem diagnosed in four lifeguards. `` I have my fingers and toes crossed that maybe this will give us the answers we're looking for,'' said <PERSON> Pierrette </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, the city's risk-management officer Two lifeguards were diagnosed last month and two were diagnosed last week with hypersensitivity pneumonitis, a rare allergic reaction to prolonged exposure to various organic dusts and chemicals. `` They're sick in that they feel tired all the time, just like if you have a real bad case of the flu,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said. The four lifeguards also have runny noses and runny eyes. Three were assigned other city jobs and one quit to return to school. `` In my mind there's no doubt there's a problem with the pool. But we do n't know what it is,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Cecile </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> of the National Jewish Center for Immunology and Respiratory Medicine in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. She diagnosed three of the four cases. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> will test water samples shipped them Monday for a small protozoa called acanthamoeba, which has been associated with the disease, said <PERSON> Govinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Visvesvara </PERSON>, research biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s division of parasitic diseases. Some types of the protozoa are resistant to chlorine. Water and air tests so far have turned up no cause for the illnesses. Results of the additional tests were expected in two to three weeks. The indoor pool was closed pending the additional test results and to avoid