<HEAD>Democrats Invite Walesa to Address Congress, Outline Aid Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was invited to address a joint meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday as <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats announced an ambitious effort to help <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> make the leap from communism to democracy. Democratic leaders of both chambers dismissed President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s $ 219 million package of initiatives in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a `` grossly inadequate'' response to an historic opportunity to bolster democracy and free enterprise in the region and to end the 40-year Cold War with victory for the West They spelled out a legislative program _ with a potential total value of more than $ 3.7 billion _ composed of loans from international financial institutions, direct American aid and loans and a five-year halt in Polish payments on its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank debt. `` Bold action today will be far less costly than timidity,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>. `` For if we hesitate, and the opportunity is lost, we will be paying for it for a long, long time _ in an escalating arms race ...'' Escalating the partisan attack on Republican inititives for <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said it is ironic that a government which doubled <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spending to respond to a Soviet military threat, `` now seems curiously paralyzed, unable to respond to the possibility of economic freedom, democracy and peace breaking out in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> ...'' But <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON>, assistant secretary of State for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> affairs, denying such paralysis exists, said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s new plan for restructuring its centralized economy is `` in many respects a declaration of economic independence.'' <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> that a Polish request for a $ 1 billion loan to stabilize the economy is `` under very active review at very high levels. There will be a response to that shortly.'''' The invitation to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to address a joint meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 15 was extended by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who had already announced plans to visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, is expected to accept. Both Democratic leaders compared the proposal to the aid announced so far by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, with <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> calling the president's `` woefully inadequate. `` The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> program is grossly inadequate,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich. `` We intend to provide the leadership that has been lacking up to now. The Democratic aid package includes $ 887 million in new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic and food assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, of which it is contemplated that $ 415 million would be appropriated for use in the 1990 fiscal year which opened on Sunday. This would include some $ 125 million in immediate food aid. The plan builds on and expands the private-sector Enterprise Fund proposed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during his visit to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> last summer. It would help fund a host of small-scale projects, encourage joint commercial ventures with Western corporations, and work to establish private businesses in the two countries. The Democratic aid plan includes trade credit insurance, health programs, scholarships and scientific and labor exchanges. It calls for a coordinated aid effort by the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export-Import </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. It calls for the use of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Exchange Stabilization Fund to make available up to $ 1 billion in loans to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` Our package will instruct the secretary to use that fund for bridge loans to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, which they can use to repay debts, buy the materials necessary for industrial restructuring, and jump start their economy,'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> said. The plan would also give <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> breathing space by halting, for five years, payments on its $ 2.5 billion debt to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lending institutions. Another element of the proposal would instruct <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representatives to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to seek $ 1.4 billion in bridge loans for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.
