<FIRST>r a AM-ResearchEthics     10-03 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Research Ethics,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Journal Tightens Ethics Standards for Researchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spurred by concerns about scientific misconduct, a prestigious medical journal will require study authors to hand over their raw data for examination if requested, the journal editor said Tuesday. The journal also will tighten its requirement on disclosing financial interests involved in the research, said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> of the Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The steps are among requirements being imposed to protect the credibility of the journal, <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. The requirements will take effect when they are announced in next week's issue, he said at a science reporters conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're calling attention to all these things, hoping by education or intimidation to keep things straight,'' he said in an interview. To get research published in the journal, scientists will have to sign a pledge that they will let editors examine their raw data if the editors ask for it, <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. That will help in detecting misrepresentation of data or fraud, he said. The journal already asks authors to disclose financial interests in their work, and `` we've trusted authors to level with us,'' <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. The journal will go a step further by requiring a signed certification. Financial interests include who paid for the research, who employs the researchers, whether a researcher owns stock in a company that would be affected by the study and whether the scientist is a paid consultant to such a company. Such information may be published along with the study, <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. Study authors also will have to certify that they participated in the reported work enough to take public responsibility for it. <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said that is aimed at the practice of `` honorary authorship,'' in which a listed author may not have played a meaningful role in the study. In some recent medical fraud cases, distinguished scientists who were listed as authors had never seen the paper and did not even know the reported research was bogus, he said. But the appearance of their names on the papers lent the works credence, he said. Authors also will have to vouch for the validity of the study and certify that they had reviewed and approved the final manuscript. If an author lies in making the newly required statements, the journal may publish a notice about it, <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. In a separate presentation at the conference, a prominent heart disease researcher said federal funding for biomedical research should be set as a fixed fraction of the nation's spending on health care. Without such steps to assure adequate funding in the future, the field will have trouble attracting young researchers and replacing antiquated equipment, said <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotto </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Baylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. That in turn would endanger its ability to conduct the science that leads to new products for health care, he said. In 1985, the nation spent $ 458 billion, or about 10.8 percent of its gross national product, on health care costs, he said. Federal funding of medical research has declined to about 1.2 percent of overall GNP from previous levels of 3 percent, he said. A return to the previous level might be an appropriate target, he said. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, associate vice president for medical research of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed the fixed-percentage idea is `` not very realistic politically.'' It would convert research funding to an entitlement like <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would probably be reluctant to do that, he said in an interview.
</TEXT>
