<HEAD>State Department Asks For Freer Flow Of Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration urged <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> on Tuesday to work out an agreement with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> permitting the emigration of thousands of additional refugees who have flocked to <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>'s embassies in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. But the best solution, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said, would be for the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to establish permament procedures for people to travel `` without hindrance from their government.'' Under an agreement between the two Germanys, more than 6,000 East Germans were admitted to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> over the weekend. Afterward, thousands of additional would-be emigrants went to the West German embassies in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> trying to follow their countrymen. However, the East German government said the agreement was a one-time humanitarian arrangement and demanded that <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> not allow the second influx to stay in its embassies. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, through <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, came down Tuesday on the side of the refugees by invoking the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreement, a 35-nation accord that pledged a freer flow of people and ideas between East and West. Having signed the accord, <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said, the East German government is `` responsible to meet that commitment.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official also praised <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for providing a home for fellow Germans. But the statement read by <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> also suggested that <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, one of the strictest Communist states in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, could help keep its people from leaving by undertaking reforms. `` We believe that in order to remove the conditions which caused so many people to flee to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, the GDR -LRB- <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Democratic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> -RRB- leadership should institute reforms which will lead to a political and economic system responsive to the population of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said. He said the `` root cause'' of the situation was that people do not want to live in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` If you're going to have a way of resolving the situation in the long run, there are going to have to be political and economic reforms in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> that will make it a more livable place for people.'' Still, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official stressed the view that East Germans under the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> agreement have a right to go to the West. <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said the agreement specified `` a very clear freedom to travel and freedom of emigration.'' On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, meanwhile, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> G.H </PERSON>. <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON> reaffirmed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the eventual reunification of East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> but said that reunification must be approached cautiously. `` It is correct that the history of the 20th century is a history in which the unification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> led to instability and to war. History tells us to be very cautious,'' <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON> said at a congressional hearing.
