<FIRST>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     10-03 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn-Soviets,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy 2 Million Tons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought 2 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, the first for delivery in the just-begun marketing year under a long-term supply agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Rumors had been circulating in the grain trade that the Soviets were in the market for a large order of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn. The seventh year of the long-term agreement between the two countries began on Oct. 1. Officials said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain sales to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1988-89, the sixth year of the agreement, were a record of more than 21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat. In addition, 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of soybeans, 1.35 million tons of soybean meal, and 1.02 million tons of grain sorghums. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 2 million tons of corn would be about 78.8 million bushels. The sales were made by unidentified private exporting companies, who are required by law to report large sales to the department. No selling prices or further details were released. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.22 per bushel at the farm level, according to the department's five-day average, meaning that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $ 175 million. The agreement was extended last year until Dec. 31, 1990. Meanwhile, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are preparing to begin preliminary talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Dec. 4 for a new long-term agreement to succeed the current pact. Under the current agreement, the Soviets are committed to buy at least 9 million tons of grain annually, including a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn, and 1 million tons which can be wheat, corn, soybeans and soybean meal, or any combination of those. The pact also allows <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to buy up to 3 million tons of additional wheat and corn annually without further discussions. If more than 12 million tons are wanted, however, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must be consulted.
