RSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bricklayers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Craftsmen </ORGANIZATION>, said `` There has been a paralysis of leadership on both ends of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> on the housing problem. Housing for the homeless is the most obvious of concerns ... but ordinary people, working people, simply can not afford housing today.'' According to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, there are an estimated 3 million homeless people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> today. Though that figure has been repeatedly cited as gospel by march organizers and some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, it is widely disputed. The liberal <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, for example, said in 1988 that the homeless numbered no more than 600,000. Other estimates abound. A recent report by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affordable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said `` the number of persons likely to be homeless on a given night vary from 655,000 to 4 million,'' and it put the annual growth rate of homelessness and anywhere between 20 percent and 40 percent. Activists complain that the Reagan-Bush administrations cut the budget authority for federal housing assistance programs by 77 percent _ from $ 32 billion to less than $ 8 billion a year _ and cite that as the principal reason for the growing numbers of people who sleep in bus stations, abandoned cars, cardboard boxes or on heat grates. But the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> says that while budget authority _ the spending limit _ was lowered, actual spending increased almost 150 percent since 1978. Still, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s own figures indicate that at least 25 million Americans spend more than half their income on housing. Currently, one in four eligible poor renters actually receives federal help. Some conservatives, including former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, have argued that many of the homeless are mentally disturbed people who are on the streets, not for lack of government or private resources, but because of recent court decisions which prohibit them from being institutionalized against their will. But the <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> study says that `` Unlike the former stereotype of the Bowery Bum or the lone drifter, today's homeless are, substantially, functioning adults and families with children. They are a cross-section of our poverty population.'' According to the <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, between 500,000 and 750,000 children in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are homeless. Though all participating organizations have vowed their activities will be peaceful, one of the more militant groups, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homeless </ORGANIZATION>, has threatened to `` evict'' <ORGANIZATION> H