<HEAD>Experts Urge Congress to Accelerate Fusion Energy Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leading experts on the potential for harnessing the energy that makes the sun and stars shine told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday the government should speed the pace of experiments that could produce a breakthrough in the next decade. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Furth </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plasma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that government leadership for the magnetic fusion program was floundering just as scientists neared the most important experimental stage in 40 years of work. `` At the moment, there is no schedule'' for beginning the next key experiments, <PERSON> Furth </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, Space and Technology subcommittee on investigations. He said that while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the wherewithal to be a world leader in magnetic fusion research, `` we're suffering from some kind of psychological block'' that prevents the nation from making the necessary commitment. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has spent $ 5.5 billion in taxpayers' money over the last four decades in pursuit of magnetic fusion energy _ a self-sustaining reaction that releases energy when isotopes of hydrogen are heated to temperatures hotter than the sun's core and then fused. Magnetic fields are used to confine the isotopes. No one yet has proven the process to be commercially feasible, but many believe it could be the major source of electricity generation by the middle of the 21st century as the nation seeks to lessen its dependence on fossil fuels. The next big step in fusion research, the experts told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, Space and Technology subcommittee on investigations, is building a Compact Ignition Tokamak _ the world's first device capable of producing a fusion reaction in which enough heat is generated to sustain the reaction without further heating by the machine. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had proposed that construction of the Compact Ignition Tokamak start in 1992, but the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in recent months has indicated it wants to spend less on the machine and more on trying to determine beforehand whether it would work. It has not set an official timetable for construction. <PERSON> Furth </PERSON> and other experts said building the $ 400 million machine was vitally important to the program, even if the machine's success could not be assured in advance. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Overskei </PERSON>, senior vice president of the fusion division of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomics </ORGANIZATION>, told the panel that achieving a self-sustaining magnetic fusion reaction was possible in the 1990s and `` will put us on the threshold of fusion energy production.''
