<SECOND>AM-AIDS Virus,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Find First Western U.S. Case of Type 2 AIDS Virus Infection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first western <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> case of a rare type of AIDS infection was diagnosed in a man who had sex with 20 to 40 women here since 1979, but the risk to his lovers is fairly low, doctors said Tuesday. The man, who has n't developed AIDS, `` is definitely the first case I know of on the West Coast'' of infection by HIV-2, a relative of the AIDS virus which is rare in this country compared with the main AIDS virus, HIV-1, said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, an epidemiologist at the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. Until now, only seven cases of HIV-2 infection had been confirmed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ three in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and one each in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> _ and three of the patients developed AIDS symptoms, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said by phone from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Almost all the patients imported the virus from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where HIV-2 is endemic. Of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> man's lovers, `` We've identified one individual with whom he had multiple unprotected sexual contacts over a long period of time, and that person has been tested and is not infected with this virus. That is reassuring,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerndt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s director of AIDS epidemiology. A second lover also is uninfected, but officials expect to locate only two or three more of the 20 to 40 women with whom the man had sex since he moved here in 1979 from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nation of <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leone </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kerndt </PERSON> said. The infected <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> resident is in his 30s, works full-time and attends school part-time. Officials withheld his identity. He has refrained from sex since learning three months ago he might be infected with HIV-2, said Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON>, AIDS virology laboratory director at <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` This man is a pretty decent person,'' <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> said. `` He's had a couple of traceable contacts and they are negative -LRB- AIDS-free -RRB-. But he had multiple other non-traceable contacts _ one-night stands. He's fully cooperative, but he does n't know these other women he had casual sex with.'' A private doctor referred the man to <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS testing, but he was n't hospitalized, <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> said. HIV-2, or human immunodeficiency virus type 2, was first described in 1985 in West African prostitutes who had no symptoms, then was reported in 1986 in two West Africans who suffered AIDS, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. HIV-1 and HIV-2 both can cripple the body's ability to fight disease, leading to fatal infections and cancers. `` The question that remains is whether it -LRB- HIV-2 -RRB- can lead to immunodeficiency as quickly or as often as HIV-1,'' which has caused AIDS in more than 105,000 Americans, killing some 61,000 of them, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. The infected <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> man has very low levels of HIV-2 in his blood, so `` the risk of transmission in casual sexual contacts is very low,'' <PERSON> Kerndt </PERSON> said. He said the man may have been infected before coming to the country in 1979 or during a visit home in 1983. <PERSON> Kerndt </PERSON> said the infected man never donated blood, `` has not used drugs intravenously, nor has he engaged in any homosexual activity.'' So far, the risk to the blood supply is considered low because blood bank guidelines prohibit blood donations by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION>, and because the test used to detect blood infected with HIV-1 can detect 85 percent to 90 percent of samples of blood infected with HIV-2, <PERSON> Kerndt </PERSON> said. HIV-2 and HIV-1 are equally common in the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, and HIV-2 may be more common in <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bissau </LOCATION> and perhaps <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>, <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said, adding that HIV-2 infection also has been reported in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and other parts of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
