<HEAD>Court Hears Arguments on Exclusion of Evidence in Illinois Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police misconduct is likely to increase if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> creates a new loophole in the rule barring unlawfully obtained evidence from criminal trials, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawyer warned Tuesday. `` Expansion of the use of unlawfully obtained evidence ... is a major step the court should not take at this time,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, arguing in behalf of a young convicted murderer before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` It would add significant incentive to police'' to violate protected rights, he contended. But <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Madsen </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general for <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, said the justices would enhance the `` truth-seeking process'' of criminal trials nationwide if allowing such an expansion. The state's arguments are supported in a `` friend-of-the-court'' brief submitted by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. At issue in the case, to be decided by July, is whether statements a criminal defendant makes after an unlawful arrest may be used by prosecutors to contradict a defense witness' trial testimony. The so-called `` exclusionary rule,'' created by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> nearly 75 years ago, generally prohibits the use at trial of any illegally obtained evidence. The high court later carved out an exception to the rule by allowing prosecutors to use such evidence to contradict a defendant's own trial testimony. But the justices never have said such evidence may be used to rebut or discredit other witnesses' testimony The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 4-3 vote, allowed such evidence to be introduced at the trial of <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, sentenced to 30 years in prison for a 1982 murder. <PERSON> James </PERSON> was 15 when arrested in his mother's beauty parlor for a pair of Aug. 30, 1982 shootings. He was tried as an adult. Prosecutors said <PERSON> James </PERSON> shot and killed <PERSON> Geliria </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> and wounded another youth in a late-night confrontation on a south <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> street. Several prosecution witnesses identified <PERSON> James </PERSON> as the triggerman, and testified that on the night of the crime he had long, reddish-brown hair. At his trial, <PERSON> James </PERSON> had short, black hair. <PERSON> James </PERSON> did not testify but two defense witnesses testified in his behalf. One said that <PERSON> James </PERSON> had short, black hair the night of the shootings. Prosecutors then won the judge's permission to let a police detective testify that <PERSON> James </PERSON>, when arrested, said he had long, reddish-brown hair the night of the crime and that he had his hair dyed and cut at his mother's shop. The trial judge previously had disallowed such testimony, ruling that <PERSON> James </PERSON>' arrest was unlawful because police at the time did not have a court warrant or probable cause to suspect him of committing a crime. <PERSON> Madsen </PERSON>, the state's lawyer, was questioned rigorously by Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, the court's only <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> native. If unlawfully obtained evidence can be used by prosecutors any time a defendant mounts any kind of defense, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> suggested, `` police would have every incentive'' to bend the rules. `` Police departments around the country would alter their procedures'' to make sure such evidence is obtained, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Madsen </PERSON> disagreed, saying, `` It's not correct to presume that the police would not do it right.'' The case is <PERSON> James </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>, 88-6075.
