<HEAD>Communist Party Calls Congress for January</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to include Nalec quote; picks up 6th `Seventy-two
percent...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communists decided Tuesday to hold a congress in January, which could be their last because a poll of members indicates 72 percent want the party completely reorganized and given a new name. The <ORGANIZATION> Eleventh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was scheduled for Jan. 27 by a resolution accepted at a one-day meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The committee also called for congress delegates to be elected under new democratic rules. The party, officially called the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was established in its current form in 1948. After crushing election losses this year, party leaders seem determined to rename the party and create a broader leftist political organization that would include socialists and social democrats. `` People from under different shades of the red banner'' should be able to `` find their place in it,'' party Secretary <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> told the committee Tuesday. The party should become `` open to reality and to the challenges that the future brings,'' he said. <PERSON> Tomasz </PERSON> <PERSON> Nalec </PERSON>, who represents a reformist club within the party, said the full party meeting should be considered `` the founding congress of a new party of democratic socialism.'' Seventy-two percent of party members polled over the past month favor changing the party's name, charter and program, according to partial results announced at the plenum's opening. The survey involved more than 1.1 million of the 2.1 million party members. Officials of the party, seeking to recast its identity since overwhelming losses to Solidarity in June's first-ever democratic parliamentary elections, say it must change to survive. Politburo member <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Orzechowski </PERSON> has said the party should rename itself the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Working </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>. The key changes are to be made at the congress, expected to be made up of 1,000 to 2,000 elected delegates under the leadership of First Secretary <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>. A communist official who briefed reporters before the plenum on condition of anonymity also said another shakeup in the party's ruling Politburo was expected It would be the second since July. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, discussing preparations for the congress at the plenum, said the party planned open, competitive election campaigns for congress delegates in order to get the public interested in the party's affairs. The party is inviting society to `` create the party with us,'' he said, and the party must strive to find an identity which will give it a popular base. `` The question is whether the Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> can fulfill the aspirations of the part of Polish society which is left-leaning,'' he said. The pro-Solidarity newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that the draft plenum's resolution favored a multi-sector economy dominated by development of the state-run economy. The draft opposed privatizing and selling off state enterprises, a chief economic goal of the Solidarity-led government, the newspaper said. The draft also `` obliges all party cells to create conditions for free expression of different views,'' the newspaper said.
