<FIRST>r a AM-APME-Hammond     10-03 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-Hammond,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historian Sees `Community of Interest' in War Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A `` community of interest'' between government and the news media often limits war coverage, a historian who has studied Vietnam War reporting told newspaper editors Tuesday. Military historian <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> has stirred controversy with his book `` The Military and the Media'' by contending that, overall, news accounts of the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War gave a better picture of that conflict than did official reports. But he says the news media passed over some major stories. `` The media is much less an outsider from the government than, perhaps, it might think,'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> told the annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors. `` There's a tremendous interplay between the government and the media. Not only do individuals constantly go from the media into government, or from the government into media ... but there is a community of interest here.'' <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, a historian at the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said reporters operated with self-imposed limitations in reporting the Vietnam War, to avoid burning bridges with military authorities. `` He's going to have to be back over there again dealing with them to get some more news,'' he said. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said, news accounts sometimes informed senior military commanders of what actually was happening in the war. `` Sometimes the commander high up the chain of command is the last one to find out anything,'' he said. News coverage often prompted a change in tactics that benefited the war effort, he said. `` In this case, media coverage actually extended the vision of the commander, and he was able to make a response that was very important to the overall goal of the American military in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.'' But major stories that would have bruised the Army's image went largely unreported, including the persistent problems of the M-16, the primary infantry weapon used in the war, he said. Far from assisting in the war, that lack of reporting may have damaged the military effort because there was no call for changes to the M-16, <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> said. `` The press in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> did not pick up the story with any consistency,'' he said. `` What happened? The military never had any kind of a prod to do much about repairing the weapon.'' The <ORGANIZATION> APME </ORGANIZATION> comprises news executives of the member newspapers of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the newsgathering cooperative.
