<TEXT>
 Snow fell in the mountains of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, but it was mostly dry weather for the eastern half of the nation except for a few showers in the Northeast. <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, reported 5 inches of snow on the ground by Tuesday morning, and 1 to 3 inches of new snow was expected above 5000 feet in the <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s south central and southwestern mountains of montana. Snowfall of 4 to 7 inches was expected above 7500 feet in the northwest mountains of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s eastern mountains expected 2 to 4 inches through Tuesday night. Snow in the higher elevations of the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> range of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> was gradually coming to an end, but the same storm system kicked up wind gusts to 45 mph in northern and central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. Widely scattered rainshowers extended from south central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> across parts of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> while a few showers lingered in the Northeast. Otherwise, dry weather prevailed east of the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. Dense fog was reported early Tuesday In <LOCATION> pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and along the coast of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Fair skies were over much of the rest of the central and eastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The nation's north central and northwestern regions had record low temperatures for the date in a dozen cities. <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, recorded a low of 16, eclipsing the 24-degree mark of 1935; <LOCATION> 