<HEAD>Tropical Depression Thirteen Weakens in Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> tropical depression that forecasters originally feared might strengthen into a tropical storm broke up Tuesday. `` I do n't think we're going to have to worry about it any longer,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Molleda </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION>. At 6 p.m. EDT, forecasters said the latest satellite pictures showed the depression was no longer identifiable due the strong upper level winds that developed over the system throughout the preceeding 12 hours. No more advisories would be issued on the system unless it regenerated, which was not expected, the center reported. The depression, the 13th of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, formed Monday. Forecasters earlier had warned the system could intensify to tropical storm strength by Tuesday. At noon EDT, the system had top sustained winds near 35 mph and was centered near 17 degrees north latitude and 50 degrees west longitude, about 800 miles east of the <LOCATION> Leeward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. When a system's maximum sustained winds reach 39 mph, it becomes a named storm, and is classified a hurricane at 74 mph. Hurricane Hugo was the eighth named storm and the fifth hurricane of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season, which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
