<HEAD>Wounded Salvadoran Guerrillas Seek Asylum At Mexican Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forty-eight wounded guerrillas, most of them amputees, moved Tuesday to the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> from the Metropolitan Cathedral they had occupied for six weeks. The occupation began Aug. 20 with eight wounded entering the church and the number had reached 48 by last weekend, annoying both the rightist government of President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> leaders. `` The cathedral is not a hotel,'' Monsignor <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> <PERSON> Damas </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, said late last month in an appeal to vacate the church. The guerrillas had said they would stay in the cathedral until they and wounded comrades on battlefronts were given safe conduct out of the country for medical treatment. But <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> <PERSON> Damas </PERSON>' chagrin apparently changed their minds. Red Cross vans took the 46 men and two women from the cathedral to the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. One man who said he lost his right arm in combat, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> through the embassy gate the wounded will not comment on future plans until arrangements were worked out with the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> ambassador. Access to the embassy was barred. Repeated telephone calls went unanswered. Earlier, insurgents denounced <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s speech Monday to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in which he called for a cease-fire in the 10-year-old civil war. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who took office June 1, said his government would propose a complete cessation of hostilities during peace talks with rebels scheduled for Oct. 16-17 in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, umbrella for five guerrilla groups, has insisted an agreement must be reached on democratic reforms before the war can end. <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Villalobos </PERSON>, a rebel negotiator, said, `` We want democracy and peace. It must be in that order, because if peace comes before democracy, it will be the peace of the cemetery.'' The rebels demand an end to what they call official repression, an overhaul of the judiciary and reduction of the armed forces. `` <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> filled his speech with words like human rights, peace and democracy. At the same time what we're seeing is a wave of arrests of members of popular organizations ... tortures, disappearances and murders,'' said the rebels on their clandestine Radio Venceremos. Vice President <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> told journalists Monday the call for a cease-fire `` is not a call for the surrender of the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>.'' He said a cessation of hostilities `` would create appropriate conditions for the search for lasting peace.'' The rebels observed an 11-day unilateral cease-fire between Sept. 13-23 for the preliminary talks. They accused the government of taking advantage of the truce to move forces into guerrilla-controlled zones and arrest leaders of labor and peasant organizations considered guerrilla fronts by authorities.
