<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Alaskana Adv06   10-03 0892</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Alaskana, Adv 06,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Oct 6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Everything About Alaska Can Be Found in New Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SITKA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The unassuming facade of The Observatory gave no hint of the significance of what was inside. But like a good book, <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON>'s bookstore could not be judged by its cover. Inside was a collection that had become a treasure to book and map collectors worldwide. <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON>'s specialty is `` Alaskana'' _ books, maps and prints that tell of the Last Frontier's colorful past. The treasure still exists, but not in this scenic fishing port and mill town along southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s rain forest coast. <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION> and its 8,000 residents recently lost the best collection of literary Alaskana to <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> For <LOCATION> Longenbaugh </LOCATION>, 55, the move south represents a return to her roots. She grew up in northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` It's very, very interesting, because I have lived in <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION> for 26 years,'' she said. `` So am I still a northern New Mexican? Am I an Alaskan? Do n't know. Got ta go down and find out.'' <LOCATION> Longenbaugh </LOCATION> does n't plan to open her new store until later this year. But she expects it will offer more space than the cramped quarters of her <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION> shop, where the lack of order was enough to make a librarian faint. Thousands of books were crammed on shelves, stacked on the floor and buried under desks _ everywhere except on a narrow ribbon of linoleum that snaked through the shop's two small rooms. The hand-printed signs that separated the books by subject did little to alleviate the disheveled appearance. <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON>'s passion for out-of-print books long ago overcame any passing interest in library science `` I'm at the other end of the spectrum from the book dealer who has thousands of volumes and knows where every one is,'' she said recently before the move. <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON> began to turn her love for books and fascination with polar-region history into a business 13 years ago. Her children were growing up and she was looking for something fun and profitable to do with her time. She started trading books from her home on a tiny island off <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION>'s waterfront, but soon realized she needed a store. In 1977, she rented a small house on a back street and converted it into The Observatory with 343 out-of-print books on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Today she has about 3,000 volumes on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, 6,000 on other subjects, 2,200 historic prints and maps, and dozens of reference books. She began trading in maps and prints in 1979 after a buying trip to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. `` I kept noticing in little towns there would be a little print and map shop,'' she recalled. `` I thought, ` Gosh, I wonder if anybody in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> would be interested in old maps of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>?''' They were. Alaskans comprised about 50 percent of <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON>'s clientele About 40 percent were from other states and about 10 percent traded from overseas. With virtually no advertising, the self-taught historian-bookseller built an international business. She remains somewhat perplexed about how she became so well-known among book and map collectors. `` I do n't know,'' she said. `` Word of mouth, I think.'' Although <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON> hopes to `` go upmarket somewhat'' with her <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION> store, she easily resists being stereotyped as a highfalutin trader of rare books and maps. `` On purpose I run a democratic bookstore. My idea is that you can come into the shop and you may not see anything you like, and you can leave, but I do n't want you to say, ` There was n't anything in that place I could afford.' `` Good reading is good reading,'' she said. `` If it's an old library discard, that's OK _ the content is still perfectly good and it's fun to read.'' <PERSON> Longenbaugh </PERSON> also rejects the notion that booksellers should n't specialize in their favorite subjects `` The rule of thumb goes, you are never, never to deal in a specialty where you yourself collect, because you will cheat your customers by grabbing off the good stuff. `` My feeling is, if I dealt with something that bored me I would n't enjoy doing it. Sure, I take one now and then. But I always figure, there's another copy out there. The customer can have the next one.'' A friendly woman with a hearty laugh and insatiable curiosity, she revels in playing detective for customers seeking a particular out-of-print book. `` It's just so much fun,'' she said. `` Lots of dealers do n't like to do book searches because they are so time consuming I charge a dollar and a half, and I'm sure I spend a lot more than that.'' Her <LOCATION> Sitka </LOCATION> customers now have to request that service by mail. They also can no longer hear her classical music show on the local public radio station, or enjoy her narration of the station's daily soap opera. `` People like <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> are irreplaceable,'' said <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON>, program director for KCAW-FM. `` Her particular combination of personality and talent is something that is rare even in a big city, let alone in a town our size.'' <LOCATION> Longenbaugh </LOCATION> is touched by such sentiment. `` Bless their hearts, everybody's being really regretful. `` And I'm so pleased, because think how horrible it would be to live in a place so many years and have nobody care when you took off.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
