<HEAD>Ability of Typical American Family to Buy a Home Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An index measuring the ability of the typical American family to buy a home rose in August to the highest level in four months, a housing industry group said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said Monday its index rose to 102.2, meaning that a family with a median income of $ 32,992 had 102.2 percent of the income needed to buy a median-priced existing home costing $ 94,900. The association said the increase reflects both falling home prices and mortgage interest rates. It was the highest level since the index read 103.2 in April. The median means that half of the families earn more and half less, or that half the homes sell for more and half for less. The <ORGANIZATION> NAR </ORGANIZATION> said the median price for existing homes fell from $ 96,700, while interest rates dropped from 10.39 percent to 10.11 percent. It also said a $ 116 increase in the median income also helped raise the index. The association uses a composite rate reflecting both fixed-rate and adjustable-rate mortgages. The changes lowered the monthly principal and interest payment on a median home by $ 29 to $ 672, which represents 24.5 percent of the median family's income. By region, the median family in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> had 134.4 percent of the income needed to purchase a median-priced home; Southern families had 101.3 percent; Western families, 75.0 percent, and residents of the Northeast, 72.5 percent. Realtors President <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gribin </PERSON> said that while the index reflects improved overall buying conditions, it masks the difficulty first-time buyers continue to experience. `` In expensive areas, home prices are so out of sync with incomes that renters with no equity are pushed out of the buying market,'' he said.
