<FIRST>r f PM-CrisisManager Bjt   10-03 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crisis Manager, Bjt,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corporate Disasters Are Bread And Butter for Crisis Manager</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 His clients' industries read like an environmental hit list: nuclear energy, chemicals, hazardous waste disposal and lawn care. It's not surprising that <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> has made a big business out of crisis public relations. Companies that have turned to him for help include <ORGANIZATION> W.R. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Borden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s chemical division and <ORGANIZATION> Chemlawn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. He helped <ORGANIZATION> Kemper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> pull out of the highly regulated <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> auto insurance market without incurring fines. And he represents <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, operator of the troubled, overbudget <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, nuclear power plant. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>'s first job, of course, is to help such clients avoid debacles in the first place. `` We tell them, ` You live in a fishbowl today, and you have to expect everything you do and say is going to land on the front page of your newspaper,''' he said. `` You're not going to be able to go back to your boardroom and communicate with no one but your shareholders. Those days are gone.''' So when oil spills, radiation leaks or regulatory agencies sting, when government inspectors arrive to seize files and reporters descend to put tales of corporate wrongdoing on Page One, <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> provides damage control. He prescribes an old-fashioned remedy newly in vogue in crisis-management public relations: Tell all. Apologize if necessary. Make amends before the government and the courts make them for you. `` Full disclosure is where it's at,'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> said recently. `` Drench any kind of a crisis and any kind of a difficult story in information Get it all out very quickly, and assume it's all going to come out in the end. He argues that stonewalling only encourages reporters to dig for themselves, with help from the corporation's foes. If a company gets the facts out fast, the media will quickly lose interest in the story. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>'s nemesis is the corporate attorney. When disaster strikes, attorneys frequently counsel executives to say as little as possible and especially not to apologize, lest those statements be used against them in a liability suit. `` Often times the attorney wins, and that leads to negative stories that run on for days,'' said <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, 54, who cut his teeth in public relations as a utility company spokesman during the Arab oil embargo. `` Then eventually the company relents and decides to open up. But by that time so much damage has been done and they are so defensive that it usually works against them.'' Advice costs $ 50 to $ 200 an hour at <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>'s 5-year-old <ORGANIZATION> BMC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>. Though he has been successful, his staff of 30 is up against tough competitors, including major law firms with more specializing in `` governmental relations.'' That can mean anything from lobbying lawmakers to negotiating with regulatory agencies to running interference with the media. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal division, has launched a unit within the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Dorr </PERSON> representing companies or individuals who find themselves the targets of white collar crime investigations <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> agreed that candor usually pays. But he said he would advise the company to meet privately with government officials first. `` The worst thing, I think, for a company in trouble to do is for the CEO to go public and declare, ` We are blameless,' and then be left twisting in the wind as three weeks of negative details come out,'' <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> said. But, he warned, `` You do n't want to take a shot into the unknown and make a statement which is essentially a guilty plea toward a felony without having some notion of what the government attitude is likely to be.'' <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON>, managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> Adams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Rinehart </PERSON> public relations agency in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the way a company responds to a crisis can influence prosecutor, judge and jury. `` Did the company try to cover up or did it act responsibly? Those are issues that are legitimately put before the court,'' <PERSON> McDonough </PERSON> said. Whether the public approves of a company's response to a disaster can affect the bottom line just as much as a lawsuit, she added. Because of <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s quick, candid and aggressive response to the Tylenol poisonings a few years ago, the market share of the painkiller actually increased after the incident, she said. But <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, widely faulted for its response to the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> oil spill, was threatened with a consumer boycott.
</TEXT>
