<HEAD>Zenith Returns to Roots But It's TV Future Is Fuzzy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is returning to its consumer-electronics roots with the proposed sale of its computer unit, but the future of the last major U.S.-based television maker remains fuzzy. Both the North American television market and the stock market appear to be friendly toward <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> at the moment. But experts say there are no guarantees that the high-definition television technologies to which <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> is committed will ever find a large market, or that <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> will be able to survive in a sea of hungry foreign competitors. `` It's a good company but it's not a good business,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Magid </PERSON>, an electronics-industry analyst with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Needham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc.. Glenview-based <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday it had agreed to sell its computer unit to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> and would use the proceeds to lighten its debt load and sharpen its focus on new television The decision surprised some observers, since the company had long been rumored to be seeking a buyer for its consumer-electronics unit, by far the weaker of <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s two major divisions. But <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> received only fire-sale prices for its television business, so it decided to sell its computer division instead, which makes personal and laptop models, Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> told a news conference Monday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We are a highly leveraged company in two very tough businesses,'' he said. `` We could n't do either of them appropriate justice.'' <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s stock surged $ 3.25 to close at $ 17.25 a share Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> and industry analysts said the deal, valued at more than $ 600 million, would give <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> a solid financial base from which to continue battling foreign competitors. <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> estimated <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s total debt at $ 600 million. He said <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> will pay down all its short-term debt and a portion of its long-term debt with the money from the sale, leaving it with less than $ 50 million in proceeds to be used for other things. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> said it would use some of the cash from the sale to fund work on `` new consumer electronics and component technologies, particularly high-definition television and advanced high-resolution color displays.'' Analysts said high-definition television, which produces much sharper pictures than today's television screens, is something of a gamble given the unknown size of the market. `` HDTV is only one piece _ a futuristic piece _ of the consumer electronics pie,'' said analyst <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` And it's a piece of pie that has n't even been baked yet.'' Faced with the possibility of a foreign onslaught of <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> sets, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> proposed last year that the government take a major role in HDTV research in this country. But the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration now considers <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> just one of several telecommunications technologies worthy of federal support, said <PERSON> Eileen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON> denied any reduction in the administration's commitment to assist <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION>'s development `` There may appear to be less of a commitment only because <ORGANIZATION> HDTV </ORGANIZATION> is now being considered along with the broader issue of telecommunications,'' she said. Another Zenith technology, the flat-tension-mask video monitor, is the industry standard in the portable computer field, analysts said, and would represent a significant improvement in television picture quality if it could be enlarged, with or without accompanying HDTV components. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> envisions the flat tension mask as one component of an HDTV system. The deal to sell the computer division, which is subject to shareholder and regulatory approval, was seen as a coup for Paris-based Bull, which will acquire <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s successful and highly regarded SupersPort line of laptop computers as part of the purchase. The 10-year-old computer division, which employs 4,000 of <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s 37,000 workers, has been a bright performer for <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> during a decade that proved disastrous to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television industry. But television prices stabilized this year, halting an eight-year slide, and are expected to rise next year, due in part to a shortage of glass for picture tubes. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s computer sales have begun to sag. Last month, the company announced it was deferring employee raises as part of a cost-cutting program to combat losses from slack computer sales. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> turned a profit of $ 11.7 million last year after three years of widening losses, but had a net loss of $ 17 million for the first half of 1989.
