<HEAD>Soybean Trader Pleads Guilty to Mail Fraud at Board of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former soybean trader at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> became the 13th person to plead guilty in connection with a federal investigation into illegal commodity trading activity. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Eggum </PERSON>, 47, pleaded guilty Monday to two counts of mail fraud before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>. <PERSON> Eggum </PERSON> admitted to making a pre-arranged trade with an undercover <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotert </PERSON>. `` Eggum misled the customer'' by noting a false time for placing his order and made about $ 125 on May 19, 1988 on a `` curb'' trade, after official trading had ended, <PERSON> Rotert </PERSON> said. Also, on Jan. 5, 1989, <PERSON> Eggum </PERSON> admitted to making $ 50 for a fellow trader to make up for a mistake Eggum had made, <PERSON> Rotert </PERSON> said. `` He deliberately sold at a price below what the lot was trading,'' he said. `` He used the customer order to repay another trader.'' The charges carry a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a $ 500,000 fine, but prosecutors have said they will seek lighter sentences for those who agreed to cooperate. The trader to whom <PERSON> Eggum </PERSON> paid the $ 50 was <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Patten </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who already has entered a guilty plea for two counts of violation of the Commodities Exchange Act. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spent 2 -LCB- years investigating fraudulent trading at the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. In all, 46 traders and a clerk were indicted. Thirteen people have pleaded guilty, and three have not yet entered pleas. The rest have pleaded innocent.
