<SECOND>BC-Coffee,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil See Little Chance of Early Moves to Support World Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, the world's biggest coffee producer, dashed hopes Wednesday of any early agreement to bring the depressed world coffee market back under international control. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s chief coffee executive <PERSON> Jorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Dauster </PERSON> said there was `` no chance of having quotas again in the near future'' because members of the international coffee group ca n't come to terms on export limits that ultimately set prices. <PERSON> Dauster </PERSON> heads the <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> delegation attending talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't see any real change in the positions that led us into the deadlock,'' <PERSON> Dauster </PERSON> told reporters at a news conference. `` We should not rush into new negotiations unless we see that the elements that led us to deadlock have been removed.'' The organization Monday announced a two-year extension of the International Coffee Agreement retroactive to Sunday but without any price-support provisions. The agreement keeps in existence the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> as a forum for discussing matters of mutual concern to 41 coffee exporting countries and 18 importing countries. The organization was propping up prices in the glutted world market through export quotas aimed at supporting prices of beans at $ 1.20 per pound or more. The organization's regulatory powers were suspended indefinitely on July 4 after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pulled out in a price dispute with coffee-producing nations. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wanted an increase in export quotas for higher-quality coffees enjoyed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers. Since July, the price of coffee beans has dropped by more than 30 percent to a 14-year low, threatening a huge loss in income for producing countries such as <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and most central American nations, where coffee is one of the top foreign income earners. The suspension of quotas followed a fight among producers over export market shares. In the previous negotiations, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> resisted moves to cut its 30 percent share of the export quota to bump up the allocation of Central American producers of the popular mild arabica variety. <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, the world's second biggest producer, has led the campaign to bring back quotas, seeing increased export earnings as critical to help it finance the fight against the country's drug cartel.
</TEXT>
