<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is making the right move by giving up its global leadership in the laptop computer market but its success in the cutthroat television business is far from assured, industry experts say. The outlook for higher TV prices bodes well in the near term for <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>, which is the last major TV manufacturer based in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the second-biggest seller of color TVs. But <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s survival in consumer electronics over the long haul depends on its ability to develop innovative products while keeping its costs low and its public profile high. `` It's going to be a grunt and grind to do this thing,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an analyst with the Houston-based brokerage firm <ORGANIZATION> Rotan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mosle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. `` But now they've got the cash to do it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> announced on Monday it had agreed to sell its computer division, which includes <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> and the build-it-yourself <ORGANIZATION> Heath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> for as much as $ 635 million. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> will use the proceeds to eliminate most of its burdensome debt load. The Glenview-based company will have an after-tax gain of $ 22 million, Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> said Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 1.4 billion worth of computers last year and is the world's larget seller of battery-powered laptop computers, with 27.6 percent of the world market, according to <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION>, a high-technology marketing research firm. But in the past year, other major computer makers have introduced laptop models that compete with <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s for both consumer and defense-contract business. Faced with tough competition in both computers and televisions and unable to finance both, analysts say, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> was forced to choose between borrowing more money or selling part of the company. Unable to find a buyer willing to pay more than about $ 200 million for its consumer-electronics unit, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> opted out of the more salable computer business instead. `` I thought it was something they should do but I was n't sure they would they would do it,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassenberg </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION>, one of many analysts who applauded the decision. According to <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION>, a publication that tracks the TV industry, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> ranked second to French-owned RCA in sales of 1989 model color TVs to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealers. But its share of the market has slipped to 12 percent from 18.5 percent over the past seven years while such competitors as <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> have steadily gained market share. <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer electronics business was profitable in 1988 excluding interest costs and is expected to be $ 15 million more profitable than that in 1989, again excluding interest costs. He also emphasized <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment to high-definition television, using sharper-picture technology that some see as the future of TV. But analysts said HDTV is still several years away. And prospects for higher TV prices after nearly a decade of decline are tied to a continued shortage of glass for picture tubes and continued strong demand from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Zenith that emerges after the computer-division sale will have lots of cash and not much debt, which could make it an attractive takeover target, some analysts believe. But other say foreign television makers, the most likely suitors, would be reluctant to bid for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s last TV maker. That was what made it difficult to sell the television business in the first place. `` It's easier for a foreign company to buy the computer business because there are a lot of other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer businesses,'' said analyst <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.
