<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices surged higher on Wall Street today as investors grew more optimistic about the outlook for interest rates and snapped up blue chip and consumer stocks. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials reached a new closing high, gaining 40.84 to end the session at 2,754.56. That topped the widely-followed barometer's previous high close of 2,752.09, reached Sept. 1. The market extended its advance of Monday, when the industrial average gained nearly 21 points. Analysts said a stronger dollar and gains on the bond markets helped spark today's Wall Street performance. Bond prices moved higher on optimism that interest rates might come down. Analysts said hopes seemed to be increasing that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might soon find room to relax its credit policy further, given a relatively slow pace of economic growth and no recent sign of increasing inflationary pressures. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s policy-making body, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Open </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, was meeting today, but the central bank did not announce any decisions before the close of trading. The stocks of financial service and other consumer-oriented businesses were among the standouts in today's session, while some technology issues were among the losers. Analysts said traders were looking for issues with predictable growth.
