<HEAD>Gillette Introduces New Razor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> unveiled a new razor Tuesday and said it would support it with a $ 175 million multinational sales and marketing campaign, which the company said would be the biggest ever in the shaving industry. But analysts said the company could nick itself in the pocketbook if consumers do n't take to the higher-priced product, which <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is billing as the biggest shaving advance in 20 years. The silver and black razor, called Sensor, and featuring two spring - mounted, ultra-thin blades, will be sold starting in January at an introductory price of $ 3.75 `` We want to make sure people are not inhibited from using it because of a high price for trial,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, vice president of marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>. The system's refill cartridges will cost 25 percent more than similar blades now on the market, <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said, and double the cost of disposable razors. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said using the Sensor system would cost about $ 20 a year, compared with about $ 16 for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s Atra Plus and about $ 10 for disposable razors. The new product will be promoted in 19 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> countries, with about $ 80 million of the $ 175 million to be spent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In trading Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rose $ 1 to $ 47.87 -LCB- a share Its stock price has surged from about $ 33 a share last December, partly in anticipation of the new product. `` The big concern would be ` Can consumers tell the difference between the new system and the old?''' said <PERSON> Bonita </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, analyst with the investment concern <ORGANIZATION> Wertheim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schroder </ORGANIZATION>. `` Also, it will be more expensive to the consumer, so will the margins be as good as other products?'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> officials said last week that the new razor was developed over the course of about 10 years at a cost of some $ 200 million. Sensor is similar to <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s Atra brand, which has a pivoting, twin-blade razor head. However, Sensor's design also enables each spring-cushioned blade to move independently, which <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> says allows it to hug the skin without digging in. The Atra Plus, with two cartridges, sells for about $ 4. Many analysts declined to comment on the new product before they had the opportunity to view it first-hand. But most agreed the production costs were high. `` They spent lot of money on it,'' said <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Landry </PERSON>, analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` But historically when <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> has brought out a new blade it has been successful.'' `` Market share will be critical,'' <PERSON> Wertheim </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said. `` They will need to take enough market share to justify the expenses.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said it holds 18 patents on the product and four others are pending. <PERSON> Landry </PERSON> said the company will license the razors eventually to make a compatible blade `` but it wo n't be this coming year.'' Other razor companies were quick to point out the benefits of their own products and find fault with the new razor. `` You're still putting cold steel on your face which I understood was done away in a number of countries when they did away with the guillotine. It is not the modern away of shaving,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiam </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Remington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has aout 40 percent of the electric shaver market. <PERSON> Kiam </PERSON> added that the new product could benefit his company. `` What <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is trying to do is trade people up from disposables to systems,'' he said. `` We're in the upper end of the market and therefore it should help the growth of that entire segment.'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner-Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes Schick razors, cited the new razor's expected higher retail price. <PERSON> Schick </PERSON>'s Ultrex Plus and Slim Twin razors sell for under $ 3. `` With Sensor, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is asking consumers to pay a significantly higher premium price ... `` said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> LeFebvre </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Warner-Lambert </ORGANIZATION>'s consumer health products unit. <PERSON> LeFebvre </PERSON> also said that <PERSON> Schick </PERSON>'s total market share has risen while <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s has declined. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is indeed ` The best a man can get,''' referring to <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s advertising slogan, `` their recent sales do n't support it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said the new product was simultaneously launched in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the first such international marketing blitz for the company. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> has interests in toiletries and writing products, but its biggest stake is in razors, where it controls more than 60 percent of the world market. Analysts have said the new product would help expand market share and improve earnings for Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>, which fended off takeover attempts in recent years but had to weather major restructurings in the process. The company undertook a major restructuring after turning down a $ 4.12 billion <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> buyout offer in November 1986. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> repurchased 15.6 million of its shares to head off an attempted takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
