at the elements that led us to deadlock have been removed,'' <PERSON> Dauster </PERSON> told reporters at a news conference. Few observers expect the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> meeting to produce a new price-support mechanism to succeed the export quotas that were suspended July 4, precipitating a 30 percent drop in coffee prices. But <PERSON> Dauster </PERSON>'s remarks reinforced perceptions that the coffee market is headed lower still. <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Eskenasy </PERSON>, a market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said coffee-producing countries continue to underprice each other in a battle for market share, eliminating an incentive for coffee roasters to buy in large quantity. `` They are just buying hand-to-mouth,'' she said. `` There are a lot of cheap coffees all over the place.'' Ms. <PERSON> Eskenasy </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> recently dropped the price for its old-crop coffee, which is of lower quality than newly harvested beans, to 60 cents a pound and several other producers were selling old-crop coffee at 65 cents a pound. Hog futures rose sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in response to higher-than-expected cash prices and strengthening chart signals. Cattle futures rebounded from Monday's steep losses. Live cattle settled .08 cent to .35 cent higher with October at 71.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .35 cent higher with October at 82.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to .93 cent higher with October at 45.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .50 cent lower with February at 48.50 cents a pound. Gold and silver futures slipped lower on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as the dollar strengthened on currency markets. Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents lower with October at $ 366.90 a troy ounce; silver was 0.2 cent to 0.3 cent lower with December at $ 5.295 a troy ounce. Most energy futures advanced modestly on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly report, which showed a slight decline in refining activity, a 1.7-million-barrel increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil stocks, a 4.5-million-barrel rise in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gasoline stocks and a 112,000-barrel increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks of petroleum distillates. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 18 cents higher with November at $ 20.13 a barrel; heating oil was .10 cent to .46 cent higher with November at 59.68 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .16 cent lower to .67 cent higher with November at 56.64 cents a gallon. Wheat futures advanced while other grain and soybean futures closed narrowly mixed Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled 1 \ cents to 3 \ cents higher with December at $ 4.09 -RCB- a bushel; corn futures were unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $ 2.40 -LCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1 cent higher with December at $ 1.47 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 -RCB- cents lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with November at $ 5.76 \
