<HEAD>DJIA Hits New High As Wall Street Surgers Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Amex index close in 22nd graf; UPDATES 16th graf to
include machinists' rejection of contract; UPDATES with closing prices
throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wall Street surged to a new high Tuesday as investors, optimistic about the prospects for interest rates, scooped up blue chip and consumer issues. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials achieved a new closing high, rising 40.84 to end the session at 2,754.56. That topped the widely-followed barometer's previous high close of 2,752.09, reached on Sept. 1. Broader market indicators also scored new highs. Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a margin of about 2 to 1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 996 stocks up, 509 down and 486 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to a heavy 182.55 million shares, up from 127.41 million in the previous session. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 221.51 million shares. Analysts said Wall Street was awash with optimism about interest rates as prices rose and yields slumped in the credit markets. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s bellwether 30-year bond was up more than $ 5 in late afternoon trading, while its yield slumped to 8.16 percent from late Monday's 8.21 percent. Analysts said hopes seemed to be increasing that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might relax its credit policy further, given a relatively slow pace of economic growth and no recent sign of increasing inflationary pressures. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s policy-making body, the Federal Open Market Committee, was meeting Tuesday, but the central bank followed its usual procedure and did not announce any decisions. Strength in the dollar, which withstood central bank intervention, also bolstered prices on Wall Street Tuesday. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Acampora </PERSON>, a market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said traders were upbeat to the point that they ignored some of the financial markets' recent worries, such as weakness in junk bonds. `` This market's turning a cold shoulder to what could be concerning news for investors,'' he said. Analysts reported some program trading, but the broad advance `` despite the negatives is telling us that there's a lot of interest out there,'' <PERSON> Acampora </PERSON> said. The market extended the gains it chalked up late in Monday's session, when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average picked up 21 points The most actively traded issue on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday was <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION>, which jumped 1 -RRB- to 36 \ amid speculation that financier <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> was adding to his 11.4 percent stake in the company <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> was up 3 -LRB- to 59 -RCB- as the company's unionized machinists voted on whether to accept a new three-year contract or strike at midnight. After the market closed, it was announced that the machinists had turned down their tentative agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. Besides the blue chips, the biggest winners were consumer stocks, which boast predictable growth. <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> gained 2 \ to 38 \ and <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> soared 5 -RRB- to But those gains came at the expense of technology issues. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> skidded 2 | to 106 Analysts said the computer maker was suffering the fallout from last week's announcement that its third-quarter earnings would be below expectations. As measured by <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market gained $ 32.764 billion, or 0.95 percent, in value. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks reached a new closing high, rising 1.94 to 196.84. New ground was also broken at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the market value index closed at 393.02, up 3.36. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's industrial index moved up 4.42 to 404.44, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index gained 3.84 to close at 354.71. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose 2.09 to 477.28.
