<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices rose Tuesday, supported by concern about the unrest in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, gained 12 cents to close at $ 20.13 per 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said prices were buoyed by the turmoil in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, where soldiers opposed to Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> seized his headquarters in an attempt to oust him but loyalists counterattacked. Oil investors worried that the conflict could disrupt the movement of oil tankers through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, although they recognized that event still appears unlikely. `` What we did not see was tremendous panic, -LRB- but -RRB- it lent a steady tone to the market,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, referring to the impact of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> situation. Home heating oil futures traded on the mercantile exchange also rose. The November contract for heating oil edged up 0.10 cent a gallon to close at 59.68 cents and subsequent months posted larger gains. The November contract for unleaded gasoline slipped 0.16 cent a gallon to 56.64 cents. Subsequent months advanced, however, with the December contract gaining 0.38 cent to 55.08 cents. <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said refined product prices drew further strength from reports that <ORGANIZATION> Amerada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. 