<HEAD>Bentsen Seeks Oil, Gas Tax For Wetlands Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> and Energy committees have included a new tax on off-shore oil and gas production in pending legislation and want to use the millions of dollars in expected revenues to protect and restore coastal wetlands. Spokesmen for the oil and gas industry say, however, that drilling on the outer-continental shelf has done little to harm the Gulf Coast's troubled wetlands. They said their industry is opposed to being solely responsible for financing the proposed <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wetlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> under the provision backed by the chairmen, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>. `` Since most of the causes of wetlands losses were unintended consequences of activities that provided public benefits, an equitable solution would be to fund wetlands conservation programs out of general revenues. It is unfair to tax a single industry to address a broad land-use problem,'' <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lastelic </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. Environmentalists, however, say off-shore drilling has damaged coastal wetlands in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and although outer-continental shelf drilling may not directly cause wetlands erosion, setting up and operating support facilities on the mainland have contributed to losses of coastal marshes. Under the plan drafted by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., production from federal offshore waters would be taxed at 2 cents per 1,000 cubic feet of natural gas and 3 cents per barrel of oil Industry estimates say the plan would raise about $ 100 million annually, while the senators say revenues would be closer to $ 383 million over five years. The plan is included in <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s version of what is known as budget reconciliation legislation pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, of which <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is chairman. There have been no hearings on the plan. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said late Monday that getting the tax included in the reconciliation bill was `` the difficult part'' of moving the plan through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bill is the chief legislative vehicle for enacting spending cuts to meet budget targets. According to a fact sheet from <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>'s office, wetlands loss on the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> is critical, especially in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>'s office also said oil and gas activity is one cause of erosion in coastal wetlands, which provide habitat for migratory birds, fish and other ildlife, as well as commercial and recreational benefits `` Navigation, access and pipeline canals and other activities related to the exploration, development and production of oil and gas along the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> and on the outer continental shelf have had adverse effects on many of the coastal wetlands of the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region,'' <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>'s office said. `` Oil and gas production in the coastal areas have contributed -LRB- to wetlands losses -RRB-. I would n't say it's the No. 1 factor, but they have contributed their part,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Reffalt </PERSON>, refuge program director for the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Baly </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said natural gas is `` probably less than 10 percent of the problem.'' <PERSON> Baly </PERSON> said the natural gas industry would pay the greatest share of the tax _ accounting for 91 percent of what the association projects will be $ 98 million in annual revenues. `` At a time when 50 percent of our oil comes from foreign countries and concern about reducing our deficit from oil imports, it's difficult for us to understand why they're lessening the competitive factor for natural gas by applying a federal tax,'' <PERSON> Baly </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Feierabend </PERSON>, director of the fisheries and wildlife division at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said he would support the <LOCATION> Bentsen-Johnston </LOCATION> approach. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said Monday his plan would `` be a great thing for the coastal waters, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.''
