<HEAD>Crazy Eddie Says It Will Liquidate Remaining Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Crazy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the discount electronics chain known for its high-pitched commercials, turned down the volume for good Tuesday, announcing it would liquidate its last 18 stores. The company, which had been seeking to reorganize under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws, said it would liquidate because vendors were no longer willing to extend credit, among other factors. Without the credit, it could not keep operating, the company said. Because liabilities greatly exceeded assets, stockholders would receive nothing, it said. Trading had been suspended when the share price fell below 25 cents. Managers were told of the planned closings during a morning meeting at the company's headquarters in <LOCATION> Edison </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Crazy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eddie </ORGANIZATION> store here. `` It was kind of like a load being lifted off your shoulders,'' he said. The announcement ends a turbulent 20-year history for the company founded by high-school dropout <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antar </PERSON> with a lone store in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>. At its peak, <PERSON> Crazy </PERSON> <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> had 43 stores in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> They employed 1,500 people and once brought in sales of $ 300 million. The company's stock reached $ 21 a share. The tag line `` Our prices are insane,'' screamed so often on television and radio spots by former disc jockey-actor <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, made the chain known to millions. But a rift among Antar family members who served as executives, declining demand for electronics, tougher competition and seeming disorganization brought on severe financial woes. Antar, who brought the company public in 1984, later sold much of his stock, and resigned as president but stayed on as chairman. He dropped from sight and never granted interviews. Dissident shareholders, led by turnaround specialist <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> electronics retailer <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Zinn </PERSON>, took control of the company in November 1987 and found a huge inventory shortfall. Nearly three months after <PERSON> Crazy </PERSON> <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> sought bankruptcy protection in June, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> accused Antar and top management with insider trading and systematically doctoring financial figures to inflate earnings. The scheme allegedly involved exaggerating inventory and falsely reducing bills to suppliers. Meanwhile, at the store here, the floor contained compact disc players and other stereo equipment in their boxes and pyramids of Mr. Coffee machines. <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> said he wanted to show customers that the store had goods to sell, but conceded that the stock room was far from brimming over. `` This is my job, my livelihood,'' said <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>. `` But you've got to make the best of it,'' he said, confident he could find work in the computer industry. <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON> vowed to go out of business in the `` Crazy <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> tradition'' _ `` blow-out blitzes.''
