<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher in Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 11th graf bgng `In London ...' to clarify that $1.6045
dollar figure was in New York trading; picks up 12 graf `Other late ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose against most major currencies Tuesday despite continued central bank intervention as the crisis in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> boosted the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. Gold prices declined. Foreign exchange analysts said intervention by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and other central banks continued but at a less aggressive pace than last week. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrialized nations agreed more than a week ago to sell dollars and buy other currencies in a concerted effort to drive the dollar lower. `` The dollar was well bid throughout the entire day today,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Montschein </PERSON>, managing director of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` The intervention was across the board but it was n't massive.'' The seven nations in the group are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Currency analysts said the dollar's rise was led by a failure to push up the struggling yen. `` The dollar was well bid because of the yen,'' said <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>, analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Samuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` When it was unable to hold at 140 and broke above due to strong dollar demand, we saw a good variety of short covering which brought the dollar-yen up further.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 1.35 yen to a closing 140.65 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 141.10 yen, up from 139.25 late Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar traded at 141.20 yen, up from 139.70. News that the goverment of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> might have been overthrown in a coup also gave the dollar a slight kick, currency traders said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government officials later reported that the coup had failed. `` It was the flight-to-safety phenomenon,'' <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.6055 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.6175 late Monday. The pound fell to $ 1.6045 compared with $ 1.6135 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.8865 West German marks, up from 1,8795; 1.6350 Swiss francs, up from 1.6285; 1.1749 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1782; 6.4000 French francs, up from 6.3745; and 1,379.65 Italian lire, up from 1,3740 Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.8865 West German marks, up from 1.8750; 1.6350 Swiss francs, up from 1.6240; 6.4005 French francs, up from 6.3595; 2.1195 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1140; 1,380.50 Italian lire, up from 1,366.50; and 1.1763 Canadian dollars, down from 1.7772. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 365.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 366.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 365.25 compared with $ 366.40 late Monday. Gold in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> fell 75 cents to close at a bid $ 366.50. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 366.30 an ounce, down from $ 367.60 on Monday. Later Republic National bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> said gold was bid at $ 365.50 an ounce, down from Monday's $ 366.10. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 5.22 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $ 5.23. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for December delivery rose to $ 5.305 from $ 5.303.
