<FIRST>r f AM-Oil-GasOutlook     10-03 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil-Gas Outlook,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activity to Increase This Year, Decline in 1990, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least a third of the major oil and gas companies plan to spend more on exploration and production this year, but most forecast a drop in prices and activity in 1990, an industry report said Tuesday. Thirty-three percent of the major integrated companies responding to PI's annual mid-year survey said exploration expenditures this year would exceed those of 1988, while 22 percent said the expenditures would decrease, according to Petroleum Information, a Denver-based research arm of <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Thirty-nine percent of the independent operators said they would spend more on exploration, 21 percent said they would spend less and 40 percent said spending would be unchanged, PI said For the first three quarters of 1989, new field wildcat completions declined 31 percent from the same period in 1988. However, the operators' spending expectations, coupled with depressed levels of exploration activity earlier this year, indicate increased exploration in the fourth quarter, the report said. Forty-three percent of the companies surveyed said production-related expenditures would increase, 38 percent planned no change and 17 percent said they would decrease, PI said. Operators forecast a drop in prices and activity next year with the price for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate crude expected to average $ 17.45 a barrel, compared with the 1989 year-to-date average of $ 19 per barrel; the average spot price of natural gas would be $ 1.57 per thousand cubic feet, compared with the 12-month average to date of $ 1.60, the company said. The companies predicted that the Baker-Hughes 1990 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rig count would average 859 in 1990, compared with the most recent count of 978, PI said. The survey said 44 percent of the major integrated companies reported their No. 1 geographic focus would be domestic offshore prospects next year, followed by domestic onshore and international prospects. Eighty-five percent of the independent operators said domestic onshore targets would be their No. 1 priority, and 8 percent said their leading focus would be offshore prospects. The remaining operators said they would focus on international prospects. The survey findings supported a widely perceived shift toward natural gas production with 51 percent of the respondents saying they would emphasize gas prospects over oil. Nearly 69 percent of the respondents said their plans called for at least an even split between oil and natural gas. PI said 51 percent of the 1988 survey respondents said they planned such a split. Petroleum Information offers reporting services, data, data analysis and other exploration services to petroleum and related industries.
</TEXT>
