<HEAD>Union Seeks Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HORICON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The striking machinists union offered Tuesday to resume talks with <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on a new contract. `` The union is ready to meet, at their convenience,'' said <PERSON> Dwayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 873. There was no immediate response from <PERSON> Deere </PERSON>, a manufactuer of farm equipment. The union, which represents 940 workers at Deere's <LOCATION> Horicon </LOCATION> plant and another 225 on layoffs, walked out Sunday after their old contract expired. The union's negotiating committee had recommended acceptance of the company's contract offer, but the tentative pact was voted down by the rank and file on Saturday, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said a key issue was job security, although some members said they also wanted pay parity with other <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Deere </PERSON> plants. The average pay for union workers is $ 15 an hour, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Deere </PERSON>, based in <LOCATION> Moline </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, manufactures farm tractors and has other plants in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The Horicon plant is the only one whose workers are not represented by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>.
